column168: AFTER OPENING TRAILER, DISCOVERED SPILL.  CHECKED CONTAINER AND FOUND FILL CAP LOOSE.  THERE WAS JUST A SMALL AMOUNT THAT LEAKED, SO I GOT A BAG OF SODA ASH AND I NEUTRALIZED IT. column168: DRIVER HAD JUST UNLOADED AND ENROUTE TO DELIVERY SITE WHEN THE SAFETY VALVE ON TOP OF THE TANK CAME LOOSE.  PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK FROM THAT VALVE. THIS STOPPED LEAK AND CAR MOVED TO DESTINATION SAME DATE.

THE FREIGHT ARRIVED AT MPL LEAKING, THE DRUM WILL HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  DRUM HAD A STRESS CRACK IN THE BOTTOM.  SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED UP WITH SODA ASH AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.

DELIVERY DRIVER REPORTED TO HIS CENTER MANAGER, HE DELIVERED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE TO BALAZ ANALYTICAL THAT HAD LOOSE CAP.  THE CONSIGNEE OPENED THE CARTON AND DECIDED TO KEEP THE PRODUCT.  ESTIMATED LOSS WAS ONE OUNCE.  DELIVERY DRIVER WAS SENT TO THE CLINIC TO HAVE HIS HANDS CHECKED FOR SAFETY PURPOSES.  THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED BY THE CLININC WITH DUTY STATUS OK.  CONSIGNEE GAVE CENTER MANAGER THE CONTAMINATED CARTON. CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD FOLLOW-UP WITH SHIPPER.  ONE QUART MAX AUTHORIZED VIA UPS.

THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING DURING SORT.  SUPERVISOR REMOVED THE PACKAGE TO A SAFE PLACE FOR PROCESSING. PARCEL WAS OPENED AND FOUND TWO OF FOUR BOTTLES BROKE.  THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED ACCORDING TO UPS SPECIFICATIONS AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  A DAMAGE INSPECTION WAS WRITTEN UP AS WELL AS AN ISP CARD SENT TO ORIGIN DISTRICT FOR FOLLOW UP WITH THE SHIPPER.
03-05-02M PARCEL FOUND LEAKING ON CONVEYOR BELT.  REBOXED ITEMS AND SENT ON. CONTAMINATED ITEMS PROCESSED FOR DISPOSAL.

THIS PARCEL CONSISTED OF A ROLL OF FOAM AND THE 1-GALLON CAN OF ADHESIVE, BOTH OF WHICH WERE CONTAINED IN A 5' X 12" PLASTIC BAG, WITH NO PROTECTION OTHER THAN THE PLASTIC.  THERE WAS NO OUTSIDE PLACARD TO INDICATED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSIDE.  THE TOP CAME LOOSE, LOSING THE ADHESIVE.  THE FORM WAS RETURNED.  THE DAMAGED CONTENTS WERE PROCESSED FOR DISPOSAL.
PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED IN PRIMARY SORT.  ONE QUART BOTTLE HAD A LOOSE CAP. THE COMPLETE PACKAGE WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DOT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURE.

THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE A-END LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WAS DISCOVERED LOOSE AND ALLOWING A MINUTE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO RELEASE.  THE PACKING GLAND WAS TIGHTENED, THUS STOPPING THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS MONITORED FOR SEVERAL HOURS AND THEN MOVED ON TO DESTINATION.

FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED DRUM WHILE WORKING TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  PRODUCT CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM.  55 GALLON DRUM WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION FOR DELIVERY.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING WILL BE GIVEN TO FORKLIFT OPERATOR.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: 55 GALLON DRUM OF GASOLINE WAS DELIVERED TO COMPANY FOR SHIPMENT ON A CHARTER FLIGHT.  DRUM WAS WAREHOUSED FOR 5 DAYS PRIOR TO FLIGHT AND NO LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED.  DRUM WAS AGAIN INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING ABOARD AIRCRAFT WITH NO INDICATION OF LEAKING.  CLIMBING THROUGH 4,000 FEET, CREW SMELLED GASOLINE.  CAPTAIN OF FLIGHT INSPECTED CARGO AND OBSERVED SMALL FUEL LEAK COMING FROM SEAM OF DRUM.  AIRCRAFT IMMEDIATELY RETURNED TO DEPARTURE AIRPORT.  THE AMOUNT OF FUEL THAT LEAKED DID NOT EXCEED 1 PINT. DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM AIRCRAFT AND SECURED FOR PICKUP BY SHIPPER.  ARTIC CIRCLE AIR MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO FUEL SPILL, VACATED ANY GASOLINE FUMES AND INSPECTED AIRCRAFT FOR DAMAGE.  THERE WERE NO PERSONAL INJURIES NOR DAMAGE TO EQUIPMENT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: WHILE TRANSPORTING THIS AND OTHER PACKAGES TO THE AIRCRAFT, THE HILO OPERATOR FAILED TO EXERCISE CAUTION AND ALLOWED THE BOXES TO BE JARRED FROM THE VEHICLE.  THE CARTON THAT FAILED WAS DROPPED ONTO ONE CORNER WHICH JARRED LOOSE THE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THE INNER CONTAINERS.  THE HILO OPERATOR DID NOT FOLLOW ESTABLISHED COMPANY PROCEDURES FOR TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND HAS BEEN ADMONISHED.  ALL STATIONS AND DEPARTMENTS HAVE BEEN REMINDED OF THE PROPER PROCEDURE FOR TRANSPORTING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TO THE AIRCRAT. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IN A SEALED CONTAINER FOR LATER DISPOSAL.

OUR TRUCK WAS UNLOADING ONTO ANOTHER TRUCK.  WHILE PLACING THE TRANSFER HOSE ON THE VALVE FITTING THE PUMP HAD CAUSED PRESSURE TO BUILD UP.  WHEN OUR DRIVER REMOVED THE CAMLOCK CAP THIS PRESSURE WAS RELEASED CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF WASTE ANTIFREEZE TO ESCAPE ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THIS TOOK PLACE ON OUR FACILITY AT 1002 HOKE AVE, DOLOMITE, AL. WHERE OUR TRAINED PERSONNEL CLEANED THE CONTAMINATED AREA.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR PROPERTY DAMAGE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: PACKAGE WAS KNOCKED OVER BY OTHER FREIGHT.  UPON RIGHTING THE PACKAGE AN ODOR WAS NOTICED.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED A LOOSE CLOSURE ON ONE OF THE INNER METAL CONTAINERS.  THE DAMAGED PACKAGE WAS OVERPACKED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: ON MARCH 13, 1992 AT 14:05 HOURS TTAX-76227 CONTAINING FIVE TRAILERS WAS INSPECTED AT ROPER YARDS. DURING THIS INSPECTION IT WAS NOTED THAT FOUR OUT OF FIVE TRAILERS WERE LEAKING A REDDISH LIQUID, COEZ-651093, COEZ-650541, COEZ-651392, COEZ-650394, COEZ-650487 SHOWED NO SIGNS OF LEAKING.  THE RAILCAR WAS SET TO THE CIRCUS RAMP AREA AND ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO DIKE THE AREA AND CATCH THE LIQUID TO KEEP IT FROM SPREADING. MONSANTO WAS CONTACTED AND THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED TWO MEN TO THE SCENE AND THEY HIRED RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND HANDLE THE ADJUSTMENT.  ALL DEBRIS, SOAKING PADS, DIRT AND LADING WERE CONTAINED IN AN OVER-PAK DRUM AND SENT BACK TO MONSANTO ALONG WITH THE 9 DRUMS OF LEAKING PRODUCT.  EVERYTHING WAS CLEANED UP ON MARCH 16, 1992 AT 14:30 HOURS.

THE TRAILER DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS TRUCK FROM OUR WASTE OIL TANK.  HIS TRAILER OVERLOADED AND SPILLED OUT OVER THE TOP OF THE TRAILER WITH APPROXIMATELY 5-8 GALS OF WASTE OIL.  OIL DRY AND COTTON SOCKS WERE USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  NONE OF THE SPILL WENT INTO ANY NEARBY GRASS OR SEWAGE.  THE OIL DRY & COTTON SOCKS WERE CLEANED UP AND PUT INTO 30 GAL DRUMS AND WILL BE SHIPPED UNDERMANIFEST TO A SAFETY KLEEN FACILITY.

column168: UNIT 1 WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON THE BLUE GRASS PARKWAY.  AT APPROXIMATELY THE 37.5 MILE MARKER UNIT 1 LEFT THE ROADWAY ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE EASTBOUND LANE TRAVELING IN THE MEDIAN FOR APPROXIMATELY 150 FEET.  AT THAT POINT THE VEHICLE IMPACTED WITH THE GUARDRAIL IN THE MEDIAN.  UNIT 1 THEN CONTINUED EASTBOUND AND ENTERED THE WESTBOUND LANES. UNIT 1 CONTINUED 131 FEET IN THE WESTBOUND LANE BEFORE THE TRAILER OVERTURNED.  UNIT 1 TRAVELED 93 FEET MORE REMAINING IN THE WESTBOUND LANES BEFORE THE TRACTOR OVERTURNED.  UNIT 1 TRAVELED ANOTHER 94 FEET BEFORE COMING TO FINAL REST BLOCKING BOTH WESTBOUND LANES AND THE WESTBOUND EMERGENCY LANE.  AT FINAL REST THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BOTH BURNED. DRIVER OF UNIT 1 STATED THAT THE VEHICLE STARTED SHAKING AND HE COULD NOT CONTROL THE VEHICLE.  VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE TRACTOR AND ROADWAY SHOWED NO CONCLUSIVE EVIDENCE OF MECHANICAL FAILURE.  THE NELSON COUNTY POLICE WERE NOTIFIED IMMEDIATELY.  THE NELSON COUNTY EMS UNIT WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE.  LEWIS TRANSPORT PERSONNEL NOTIFIED AND IMMEDIATELY TRAVELED TO SCENE.  HERITAGE REMEDIATION CONTACTED THE CLEAN UP ANY CONTAMINATION.  IT IS THE MOTOR CARRIERS OPINION THAT THE DRIVER WENT TO SLEEP, RAN OFF THE ROAD AND OVERTURNED.  FOLLOWUP IN QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING.  DURING FUTURE SAFETY MEETINGS IT WILL AGAIN BE PREACHED THAT IN YOUR OFF DUTY HOURS YOU ARE TO REST.  ALSO, FILMS CONCERNING SKID RECOVERY AND CONTROL WILL BE VIEWED BY ALL DRIVERS.

column168: DRIVER WAS OFF LOADING DIESEL AT SULLIVAN BULK PLANT IN OILDALE.  THE OFF LOADING REQUIRED THE USE OF A PRODUCT PUMP LOCATED ON THE TRUCK TRACTOR AND POWERED BY THE TRACTOR ENGINE THROUGH A POWER TAKE OFF.  THE PUMP HAD BEEN SERVICED ON 2-29-92 AT OUR SACRAMENTO YARD.  DURING THE SERVICE, THE DRAIN VALVE SPIGOT (SAME TYPE USED ON AN OUTSIDE FAUCET) WAS INADVERTENTLY LEFT OPEN.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO CHECK TO SEE OF THE SPIGOT WAS CLOSED. HE CONNECTED HIS HOSES IN PREPARATION TO BEGIN PUMPING THE PRODUCT.  HE HAD OPENED THE CARGO TANK BUTTERFLY VALVE AND THE CARGO TANK INTERNAL VALVE AND WAS GOING BACK TO START THE PUMP WHEN HE NOTICED THE PRODUCT ON THE CEMENT APRON.  THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THE SPILL IMMEDIATELY SINCE LIGHT RAIN WAS FALLNG AND THE SURFACE WAS WET.  HE FAILED TO HEAR THE PRODUCT FLOWING ONTO THE CEMENT DUE TO THE ENGINE NOISSE.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE FLOW.  WITH ANOTHER DRIVER HELPING, THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEAN UP STARTED.  DRIVER NOTIFIED OUR BAKERSFIELD TERMINAL MANAGER WHO RESPONDED WITH SPILL SUPPLIES AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH NO CONTAMINATION.

OUR DRIVER PICKED UP THE TRAILER IN KINGSPORT, TN WHICH WAS LOADED AND SEALED.  THERE DID NOT APPEAR TO BE A PROBLEM WHEN HE PICKED IT UP AND PERFORMED HIS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION.  UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE WHEN THE DOORS WERE OPENED, THE DRUM APPEEARED TO HAVE SOME SEEPING AROUND THE FITTINGS AND THE SEAM NEAR THE BOTTOM. PETRO CHEM RECOVERY WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: DESCRIPTION OF OCCURRENCE: A HAUL TRUCK DRIVER, IN TRAINING, WITH AN ACCOMPANYING TRAINER, WAS TRANSPORTING A 40 CY CONTAINER OF URANIUM MILL TAILINGS FROM THE TRANSFER FACILITY IN THE WHITEWATER INDUSTRIAL PARK, WHITEWATER, COLORADO TO THE DISPOSAL SITE, APPROXIMATELY EIGHT (8) MILES SOUTH OF THE TRANSFER FACILITY.  AT THE TRANSFER FACILITY, CONTAINERS LOADED WITH MILL TAILINGS ARE OFF-LOADED FROM THE RAIL CAR AND PLACED ON SPECIALLY DESIGNED TRACTOR/TRAILER TRANSPORT UNITS.  THE RELEASE COMMENCED AT THE START OF A GRADE OF APPROXIMATELY 6%, 4.8 MILES SOUTH OF THE FACILITY.  THE HAUL ROAD FROM THE FACILITY TO THIS POINT IS RELATIVELY FLAT AND SMOOTH.  A COMBINATION OF DOWN SHIFTING (CHANGES OF DIRECTION OF ENERGY FLOW) AND GRAVITATIONAL FORCE CAUSED THE CONTAINER TAILGATE TO OPEN, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 1.7 CY OF MATERIAL OVER 2500 FEET OF THE ROAD SURFACE. IMMEDIATE ACTIONS TAKEN AND RESULTS: FIELD SUPERVISION INITIATED NOTIFICATION SEQUENCE, MOBILIZED RESPONSE TEAMS, SECURED AREA. ESTABLISHED CONTROLLED AREA BOUNDARIES, OBTAINED AIR AND BULK SAMPLES. SPILLED MATERIAL CLEAN UP COMPLETED AT 0130 HRS, MARCH 4, 1992.  CONTAINER TAILGATE SECURED, DIAPERED AND TRANSPORTED TO THE DISPOSAL CELL. TRANSPORT COMPLETED AT 2215 HRS, MARCH 3, 1992. CORRECTIVE ACTION ACTION: (1) CONTROL PANEL SWITCHES WERE RELABELED.  (2) ALL TRUCKS SOLENOIDS ARE BEING REPLACED.  TO BE COMPLETED BY WEEK ENDING 3/13/92.  (3) DASH PANEL LIGHTS ARE BEING INSTALLED TO INDICATE PROBLEMS WITH SOLENOID/MOTORS AND ARMING SWITCH POSITION.  (4) RETRAIN ALL DRIVERS REGARDING PROCEDURES, INCLUDING ADDENDUM TO COVER THE WARNING INDICATORS FOR THR ARMING SWITCH, LATCH/DUMP SYSTEM AND TWIST-LOCK AND LATCH/DUMP FLAGS.  (5) INSTITUTE INSPECTIONS TO ENSURE INDICATOR FLAGS ARE PRESENT AND FUNCTIONAL ON ALL CONTAINERS AND TRAILER CHASSIS.  (6) DESCIPLINED TRAINER FOR INATTENTION.

column168: ON 3/5/92, OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT FARMLAND INDUSTRIES.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO BACK INTO A DOCK.  AFTER DOING SO, HE CHOCKED HIS WHEELS AND WENT INSIDE.  ONCE INSIDE HE OBSERVED THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR REMOVING HIS LOAD DOCKS.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR THEN STRARTED REMOVING DRUMS.  AFTER ABOUT 4 OR 5 DRUMS HE STARTED HAVING TROUBLES WITH A DRUM.  OUR DRIVER AT THIS TIME DECIDED TO GO TO THE MEN'S ROOM.  WHEN HE RETURNED, HE FOUND THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR ON THE TELEPHONE.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR SAID HE HAD A LEAKER AND WAS CALLING FARMLAND'S HAZMAT TEAM.  THE SULFURIC ACID BY THIS TIME WAS RUNNING THE FULL LENGTH OF THE TRAILER AND WAS SEEPING THROUGH THE FLOOR ONTO THE REAP SECTION OF THE TRACTOR (891).  THE HAZMAT TEAM NEUTRAZLIED THE SULFURIC ACID, STEAMED OUT THE TRAILER AND STEAMED OFF THE TRACTOR.

column168: AS TRANSPORTING VEHICLE WAS ATTEMPTING TO PASS A SLOWER MOVING VEHICLE, THE SLOWER VEHICLE TURNED LEFT IN FRONT OF TRANSPORTING VEHICLE, CAUSING VEHICLE TO SWERVE AND ROLL OVER. DOW CHEMICALS' EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS SUMMONED TO THE SCENE AND USED 4 OVERPACK DRUMS TO PACK THE 4 MOST QUESTIONALBE DRUMS, ONE OF WHICH WAS SLIGHTLY LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM SEM.  NONE OF THE CHEMICAL ESCAPED THE CONFINEMENT OF THE CONTAINER/TRAILER.  NO FUTURE ACTION TO PREVENT SUCH AN OCCURRANCE IS PLANNED.

DRIVER WAS ASLEEP IN HIS TRUCK AT THE UNLOADING FACILITY.  HE WAS AWAKENED AND TOLD TO MOVE TRUCK INTO UNLOADING AREA.  AS HE BACKED INTO THE UNLOADING AREA, WHICH WAS ON AN INCLINE, HE WAS NOTIFIED THAT SOME MATERIAL HAD SPILLED FROM THE TOP OF HIS TANKER AND HAD LEAKED DOWN THE SIDE OF TANKER ONTO THE LOADING PAD (WHICH IS CONCRETE).  THIS INCIDENT WAS IMMEDIATELY REPORTED TO THE FACILITY MANAGER AND THE DRIVER'S SUPERVISOR. FACILITY PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE CONCRETE PAD AND GROUND WITH ABSORBENT. THEY CLEANED THE TANK OFF WITH TOWELS.  ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS WERE PLACED IN A FIVE GALLON PAIL FOR DISPOSAL. THE TANK WAS INSPECTED AND A VENT GASKET ON THE TOP OF THE TANK WAS FOUND TO BE DETERIORATED AND LEAKING.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED.  A MORE THOROUGH INSPECTION SHOULD ALLEVIATE PROBLEMS OF THIS TYPE IN THE FUTURE.

PAILS ON BOTTOM SKID BULGED DUE TO WEIGHT AND LET PRODUCT ESCAPE FROM THE PAILS.  AT TIME OF DELIVERY, TWO PAILS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  CONSIGNEE ACCEPTED FREIGHT AND CLEANED UP PRODUCT.  ADDITIONAL TRAINING HAS BEEN GIVEN TO EMPLOYEES INVOLVED.

column168: AT 2300 CST, MARCH 9, 1992, WERNER ENTERPRISES, INC. DRIVER DIAMOND COLLINS DISCOVERED A SUBSTANCE SLIGHTLY LEAKING AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WHILE PERFORMING A VEHICLE INSPECTION AT THE T/A TRUCKSTOP OF AMARILLO, TEXAS.  MR. COLLINS NOTIFIED OUR COMPANIES SAFETY DEPARTMENT IMMEDIATELY WITH ALL PERTINENT INFORMATION AND IN TURN THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTACT WAS NOTIFIED.  THE AMARILLO CITY HAZ MAT TEAM ALONG WITH THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICERS WERE IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 2340 CST.  AFTER A DETAILED INVESTIGATION, THE HAZ MAT TEAM CONCLUDED THAT TWO-FIFTEEN GALLON POLY DRUMS OF BATTERY FLUID, ACID HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM THE BUNG HOLE CLOSURE FITTING ON TOP OF THE CONTAINERS, AND THAT THE LEAK WAS NOT CAUSED BY EITHER IMPROPER LOADING OR FAULTY TRANSPORTATION.  WERNER ENTERPRISES, INC. THEN MOBILIZED A LICENSED SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR IN THE AMARILLO, TEXAS VICINITY, WHICH ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 0035 CST, MARCH 10, 1992. THE CONTRACTOR PLACED THE TWO LEAKING CONTAINERS AND ALL MATERIALS USED IN THE PROCESS INTO OVERPACK DRUMS, PREPARED THEM FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AND COMPLETELY DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER AND ALL OTHER CONTAINERS IN THE VICINITY OF THE LEAKING DRUMS.  AFTER THE DECONTAMINATION WAS COMPLETED, THE SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TOOK POSSESSION OF THE OVERPACK DRUMS WHICH WERE TO BE DISPOSED AS SOON AS POSSIBLE, AND OUR DRIVER WAS AUTHORIZED TO LEAVE THE SCENE.  THE PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE ON MARCH 12, 1992 WITH NO ADDITIONAL RELEASE OF THE BATTERY FLUID, ACID NOTED. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED ON MARCH 10, 1992 AT 0830 CST AND GIVEN A DETAILED REPORT ON WHAT HAD TRANSPIRED DURING THE SHIPMENT.  THE TRAFFIC MANAGER ASSURED MY CONPANY THAT THE ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEER AT THEIR FACILITY WOULD BE NOTIFIED AND THAT ALL EXISTING CONTAINERS WOULD BE INSPECTED IMMEDIATELY TO INSURE THAT THE DEFECTIVE BUNG HOLE CLOSURE FITTINGS WOULD BE CORRECTED IF NEEDED PRIOR TO ANY TRANSPORTATION.  THE SHIPPER ALSO NOTED THAT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT HAD NEVER OCCURRED IN THE PAST AND COMMITTED TO WERNER ENTERPRISED, INC. THAT THEY WOULD TAKE ALL STEPS NECESSARY TO PROTECT THE ENVIRONMENT ON FUTURE SHIPMENTS. PLEASE FIND ATTACHED HEREWITH A COPY OF THE UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST AND THE WASTE PROFILE SHEET OF THE HAZARDOUS SUBATANCE THAT WAS SENT TO THE DISPOSAL FACILITY IN LONE MOUNTAIN, OKLAHOMA.

column168: LOOSE LID CAUSED LEAK.  DAMAGED PORTION DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE.  CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD FOLLOW UP WITH SHIPPER.
DEFECTIVE TOP CAUSED LEAK.  DAMAGED PORTION DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCEDURE.  UNDAMAGED PORTION WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD FOLLOW-UP WITH SHIPPER.

BOTH BARRELS WERE IMPROPERLY DESCRIBED & LABELED.  BOTH BARRELS ARE OLD & APPEAR NOT TO BE IN DOT PRESCRIBED BARRELS.  BARRELS ARE RUSTY, SHOW SIGNS OF DRUM HEAD FLEX & ARE IN POOR CONDITION.  ONE BARREL RUBBED AGAINST THE OTHER BARREL & RUBBED ABOUT A 1" LONG X 1/8" WIDE HOLE IN BOTH DRUMS IN THE BOTTOM ROLLING HOOP.  THE PRIMARY CAUSE WAS METAL FATIGUE DUE TO THE AGE OF THE DRUMS.  LEAKAGE OCCURRED INTRANSIT TO DESTINATION.  SPILLED PRODUCT WILL BE NEUTRALIZED AND TRAILER WILL BE DECONTAMINATED PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE MANUFACTURER.  BOTH DRUMS WRE RECOOPED INTO A NEW DOT APPROVED DRUM PER INSTRUCTIONS FROM CONSIGNEE.  BOTH OLD DRUMS WILL BE HELD PENDING POTENTIAL CLAIM.  DRUMS WILL THEN BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

SHIPMENT ARRIVED EUGENE, OR ON TRAILER 15-5322.  FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON REAR QUARTER OF TRAILER.  WAS ON TOP OF OTHER FREIGHT AT APPROX 6 FT HEIGHT. NO OTHER FREIGHT LOADED ON TOP.  DOCKMAN PICKED UP CARTON AND NOTICED MOISTURE ON THE TOP.  CARTON WAS ALREADT UNLOADED.  IN OPENING CARTON IT WAS DISCOVERED THE TWO OF THE 4 GLASS CONTAINERS HAD THE LIDS BROKE OFF. ABOUT ONE QUART OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT OF EACH.  MOST OF CARTON WAS DRY. A LITTLE LIQUID GOT ON DOCKMANS GLOVES.  PRODUCT AND GLOVES WERE PUT IN SALVAGE DRUM AND HOLDING FOR DISPOSITION.
ONE CAN CRUSHED AS PALLET WAS PUSHED FORWARD TO SHUT TRAILER DOOR.  PAIL AND ALL ASSOCIATED DEBRIS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.

column168: CSXT HAZMAT ADVISED THAT FRA INSPECTOR FOUND A TANK CAR AT RADNOR YD NASHVILLE, TN LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE MANWAY AREA.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS TURNING ON TRUCK PARKING LOT.  WHEN HE CUT TOO SHORT ON THE WHEEL, STRUCK BARRIER WHICH CAUSED TO ROLL.  THE STATE WATER CONTROL BOARD WAS CALLED.  THIS INCIDENT WAS PREVENTABLE.  I DO NOT HAVE SOLUTION TO PROBLEM OF THIS KIND AS THERE WAS NO DEFECTS FOUND BY THE DOT TEAM THAT WAS ON SITE.  ENVIRONMENTAL OPTIONS WAS CALLED TO DO THE PROPER CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL OF ANY CONTAMINATED SOIL.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE UNLOADING PRODUCT, THE DRIVER TURNED AWAY TO STORE AN ADDITIVE. THE TANK OVERFILLED.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE EQUIPMENT. OFFICE PERSONNEL WERE CALLED TO THE SITE.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, K.P.N. (ROCKET) CORP., WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE SPILL WAS THEN IMMEDIATELY CLEANED-UP AND REMOVED.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING, 6" OF TOP GROUND WAS REMOVED AND PLACED ONTO HEAVY BLACK PLASTIC AND COVERED FOR ADDED PRECAUTIONS.  THE SPILL HAD BEEN CONTAINED TO A SMALL AREA WITHIN THE DIKE.  AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, THE DIKE WAS FROZEN.  THE GAS WAS TRAPPED ABOVE THE ICE IN THE DIKE.  WHEN ROCKET ARRIVED THEY REMOVED THE GAS ON TOP OF THE ICE AND THEN THEY BROKE THROUGH THE ICE AND REMOVED ALL LIQUID BELOW  WHICH CONSISTED OF A STREAM OF WATER.  ROCKET REMOVED ALL LIQUID UNTIL ONLY THE MUD REMAINED.  THE FOLLOWING DAY 6" OF TOP GROUND WAS REMOVED.  TWICE A DAY SOMEONE WAS THERE TO CHECK FOR GAS PUDDLES.  VERY LITTLE GAS WAS FOUND.  SMALL AMOUNTS AND FILMS WERE REMOVED WITH THE USE OF SORBENT PADS.  ON MARCH 4, THE WEATHER WAS MOSTLY CLOUDY, IT THEN RAINED ON AND OFF CONTINUALLY WITH A SNOW STORM ON MARCH 9.  ON MARCH 10, THE SUN FINALLY SHINED. THE GROUND WAS FROZEN, THEN IT RAINED SEVERAL DAYS, THE GAS DID NOT HAVE THE OPPORTUNITY TO SOAK INTO THE GROUND.  SINCE THIS INCIDENT, ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED NEVER TO LEAVE THE AREA OF THE SHUT OFF VALVES WHILE LOADING AND UNLOADING AS WELL AS RE-INSTRUCTION OF OTHER PREVENTATIVE MEASURES.

column42: AMMONIUM NITRATE FERTILIZERS MIXTURES OF AMMONIUM NITRATE/AMMONIUM SULFATE, WITH MORE THAN 45 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT AMMONIUM NITRATE AND NOT MORE THAN 0.4 PERCENT OF TOTAL COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL

column168: VEHICLE PULLED TO THE RIGHT ON ANDERSON COUNTY TEXAS ROAD 7711 TO MOVE AROUND A PARKED COUNTY MAINTENANCE TRUCK. DUE TO THE SOFT-ROAD SHOULDER, THE VEHICLE WAS UNABLE TO PULL BACK ON THE ROADWAY AND TURNED OVER TRAVELING AT A SPEED OF LESS THAN 5 MPH. AMMONIUM NITRATE SPILLED FROM THE TRAILER TOP HATCH DOORS AND APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF #2 DIESEL FUEL LEAKED FROM THE TRACTOR TANKS.  THE SITE WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP UNDER THE GUIDELINES OF THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRLR 17-2575 IN 161 DOOR, DOCK WORKER JON BEILE REMOVED A PALLET OF FREIGHT OUT OF THE TRAILER WITHOUT REMOVING THE LOOSE CARTON CONTAINING THIS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  AS A RESULT, THIS BOX FELL DOWN ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER FROM THE TOP OF THE PALLET AND CAUSED THE CONTENTS INSIDE TO BREAK AND EVENTUALLY LEAK OUT.  AT THIS POINT, THE DOCK FOREMAN WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SPILLED BOX OF HAZ MAT WAS LEFT IN THE TRLR AND THE DOOR CLOSED AND PLACED IN THE YARD AWAY FROM TRAFFIC BY HOSTLERS. OUR RECOMMENDATION IS THAT ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENTS SUCH AS THIS SHOULD BE LOADED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. B.O.R. INDUSTRIES RESPONDED FOR CLEANUP AND CONTAINED ALL DAMAGED PRODUCT AND CLEAN UP MATERIAL IN A SALVAGE DRUM FOR DISPOSAL, INCLUDING BROKEN GLASS AND FULLER'S EARTH.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: A NAIL WORKED UP FROM A SKID AND DAMAGED THE BOTTOM OF A 35 GALLON DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID, CORROSIVE MATERIAL UN1830.  MINIMAL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL LEAKED OUT.  DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN, SODA ASH USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE SHIPPER PICKED UP DAMAGED DRUM AT OUR SERVICE CENTER.  NO OTHER FREIGHT WAS DAMAGED.

WHILE TRAVELING TO TERMINAL FREIGHT SHIFTED CAUSING DRUM TO BE PUNCTURED ON SIDE NEAR BOTTOM RESULTING IN SPILLAGE.  WHEN DRIVER STOPPED IN YARD AT TERMINAL SUBSTANCE WAS NOTED AS LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  CLEANUP HANDLED BY CFMF TERMINAL PERSONNEL.  DISPOSAL PER SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS-THE HAZARD DISSIPATED AS THE MATERIAL HARDENS.

SLIGHT CHLORINE LEAK DEVELOPED AT DOME ON HOKX 13268.  SECTOR 20 CHLOREP RESPONDED ADN DETERMINED THAT A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF CHLORINE WAS LEAKING THRU THE RIGHT GAS ANGLE VALVE.  THE HANDWHEEL WAS TIGHTENED AND THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED, THE CAR WAS UNLOADED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. UPON RETURN TO SHIPPER, THE VALVE WAS REMOVED AND BENCH PRESSURE TESTED.  A VERY SLIGHT LEAK WAS DETECTED AT 500 PSIG.  THE VALVE WAS THEN BROKEN DOWN AND INSPECTED.  THE SEAT WAS MIRROR SMOOTH AND SHOWED NO EVIDENCE OF CORROSION OF LEAK PATH.  THE STEM HAD A VERY SLIGHT DENT IN THE VICINITY WHERE THE STEM AND SEAT CONTACT.  THIS DENT WAS THE ONLY POSSIBLE LEAK PATH THAT WAS DETECTED VIA VISUAL INSPECTION. CURRENT ANGLE VALVE REBUILDING PROCEDURES CALL FOR CAREFUL INSPECTION OF VALVE COMPONENTS FOR DEFECTS DURING THE REBUILDING PROCESS.  EMPLOYEES WHO REBUILD VALVES WERE SHOWN THE STEM TO HELP THEM IDENTIFY THIS POSSIBLE DEFECT IN FUTURE STEM INSPECTIONS AND REBUILDS.  ALL TOP VALVES ARE LEAK TESTED WITH AMMONIA PRIOR TO SHIPMENT FROM THE MUSCLE SHOALS PLANT.

column168: KENAN TRANSPORT COMPANY DRIVER HAD TWO LOADS ON TRAILER AND TRIED TO DELIVER TOO MUCH PRODUCT TO THE FIRST SITE.  THE PRODUCT OVERLFOWED CAUSING APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL.  PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE CONSIGNEE'S PARKING LOT AND THEN TRAVELLED INTO APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET OF DITCH LINE ON PRIVATE PROPERTY.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DAMMED PRODUCT IN DITCH LINE.  THE STORE WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 5 1/2 HOURS FOR THE CLEAN UP.

KENAN TRANSPORT COMPANY DRIVER WAS UNSURE OF THE SIZE OF THE UNDERGROUND TANK.  TANK FILLED AND APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF PRODUCT OVERFILLED. CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP SPILL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS, WHICH RAN INTO A GRAVEL DRIVEWAY.

KENAN TRANSPORT COMPANY DRIVER WAS TOLD BY MR. DON WILSON OF ST AUGUSTINE TECHNICAL CENTER THEAT THE TANK WOULD HOLD THE PRODUCT.  DRIVER WAS FILLING THE TANK WHEN IT OVERFLOWED WITH APPROXIMATELY 15 TO 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP THE SPILL.

THE UNDERGROUND TANK WAS FILLED TO 100% OF ITS CAPACITY.  OVERNIGHT THE PRODUCT EXPANDED AND FLOWED OUT OF THE TANK THE NEXT MORNING WHILE IT WAS BEING GAUGED.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED.  KENAN PERSONNEL ARRIVED AT THE LOCATION AND CLEANED UP THE SPILL WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS.
GASKET ON PUMP WAS LEAKING.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND CHANGED GASKET.  MOST OF THE PRODUCT WENT ONTO THE BUCKET, BUT SOME DRIPPED DOWN THE SIDE OF THE BUCKET.
3" GASKET ON THE 3-2 REDUCER THAT GOES INTO THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING. DRIVER CHANGED GASKET TO CORRECT THE PROBLEM.

column168: DOCKWORKER NOTICED ONE CARTON THAT WAS CRUSHED AND STAINED WITH MATERIAL. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS REMOVED FROM SKID AND PLACED INTO RESPONSE PACK.  NO OTHER DAMAGED WAS OBSERVED AND THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION. DAMAGED CARTON IS BEING HELD FOR PROPER DISPOSITION.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHEN DOCKWORKER WAS UNLOADING TRAILER, HE DISCOVERED ONE SKID OF MATERIAL THAT HAD APPARENTLY SHIFTED IN TRANSIT, TIPPING OVER AND CAUSING THE LIDS TO COME OFF THE CANS OF ADHESIVE.  THE MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE DAMAGED CANS WERE SEALED INSIDE RECOVERY DRUMS.
column172: Metal can, capacity 7 gallons or less

column168: DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED MATERIAL SEEPING FROM THE BOTTOM LIP ON ONE SIDE OF A DRUM AND ISOLATED THE AREA.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AND THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE CONSULTED.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER WAS CONTACTED AND ABSORBENT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILLAGE AS INSTRUCTED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.

DOCKMAN PULLED DRUM OUT WITH DRUM DOLLY AND NOTICED THE DRUM HAD BEEN STRUCK BY ADJACENT FREIGHT, CAUSING A SMALL CRACK AND LEAKAGE OF PRODUCT. THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND HELD FOR DISPOSITION.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing

THE DAMAGED CARTON HAD APPARENTLY SHIFTED IN TRANSIT, CAUSING THE INNER CONTAINER TO BREAK AND SPILL ITS CONTENTS.  THE CARTON WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND ABSORBENT WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.

column168: FORKLIFT OPERATOR PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF ONE DRUM INSIDE THE LOADING TRAILER.  WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE MATERIAL IDENTIIED.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED WITH SORBENTS.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE CARTON THAT HAD APPRENTLY OVERTURNED ENROUTE AND SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE LEAKING CARTON WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER CONTACTED.  PER THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS, THE CARTON WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND THE SPILLED MATERIAL DIKED AND NEUTRALIZED.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS THEN CLEANED USING ABSORBENT PADS AND OIL DRY.

SUPERVISOR WAS WALKING THE DOCK WHEN SHE NOTICED ONE CARTON THAT HAD APPARENTLY BEEN TIPPED ONTO IT SIDE AND WAS LEAKING MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL WAS IDENTIFIED AND THE DAMAGED CARTON REMOVED TO AN OPEN AREA. CHEMTREC WAS CALLED AND THE SHIPPER RESPONDED WTH CLEANUP INSTRUCTIONS.

WHEN DOCKWORKER MOVED DRUM FOR UNLOADING, DISCOVERED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID HAD ESCAPED THROUGH A VENT HOLE IN THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN THE TOP OF THE DRUM AND THE MATERIAL WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

DRIVER DISCOVERED ONE DRUM HAD APPARENTLY BEEN PPUNCTURED BY ADJACENT FREIGHT ENROUTE TO DELIVERY.  THE DRUM WAS TURNED UPSIDE DOWN TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE.  TAPE WAS PLACED OVER THE HOLE AND THE DRUM WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS CLEANED USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS.

DRUM WAS BEING LOADED USING A DRUM TRUCK WHEN IT SLIPPED AND WAS PUNCTURED.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED.  ABSORBAL WAS USED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE AND CLEAN THE AREA.  THE SHIPPER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO REPAIR THE DAMAGED DRUM ADNPROVIDE DISPOSITION FOR THE MATERIAL.
TRAILER ARRIVED AT BOWLING GREEN, KENTUCKY TERMINAL LEAKING.  FOUND TWO DRUMS WITH SMALL HOLES IN EACH.  SPILL PROPERLY CLEANED UP.

column168: RUPTURE DISK WAS FOUND RUPTURED IN SWITCH YARD AT AVONDALE, LA. MECHANICAL PERSONNEL REPLACED DISK.

LOAD WAS FOUND LEAKING AT AVONDALE, LA. BY ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER - INSPECTION OF LOAD INDICATED ONE 5 GALLON PAIL WAS PUNCTURED BY NAIL HEAD ON PALLET.  PAIL WAS REMOVED - TRAILER DECONTAMINATED AND RELOADED.  I SUGGESTED TO SHIPPER HE PLACE SOMETHING ON TOP OF PALLETS TO PREVENT FUTURE PROBLEMS.
column172: Plastic pail, open head, capacity 10 gallons or less

column168: 1/4" ANGLE VALVE WAS GAUGING DEVICE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN.  PLUG LOOSE. CLOSED VALVE, TIGHTENED PLUG.

column42: FORMALDEHYDE SOLUTION (FLASH POINT NOT MORE THAN 141 DEG F.; IN CONTAINERS OF 110 GALLONS OR LESS)
column168: DRUM WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT WHEN UNLOADING AND LEAKED INTO TRAILER.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK LOADING SYSTEM DEFECTIVE AT SERVICE STATION RESULTING IN SPILLAGE DURING UNLOADING PROCESS.  UNLOADING PROCESS SECURED IMMEDIATELY AT TIME OF SPILLAGE AND CLEAN VENTURES INC AND LOCAL AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED AND DEP OF NJ TO TAKE IMMEDIATE ACTION FOR PROPER CLEAN UP PROCESS.

BOX WAS DROPPED APPROXIMATELY 1 FOOT; INNER BOTTLE BROKE AND ABSORBANT MATERIAL DID NOT CONTAIN THE CONTENTS.  APPARENTLY THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT PACKED CORRECTLY, AS IT SHOULD HAVE WITHSTOOD THE REQUIRED 4 FOOT DROP TEST.

SAFETY KLEEN REPRESENTATIVE WAS LIFTING WASTE DRUM ONTO HIS TRUCK.  THE LOCK RING THAT HOLDS LID ON THE DRUM HAD WEAK SPOT IN THE METAL AND BROKE AS REP LIFTED DRUM.  I SHOWED REP HOW TO PROPERLY LIFT DRUM ONTO TRUCK, ALSO SHOWED HIM HOW TO INSPECT DRUM, DRUM LID AND LOCK RING FOR DEFECTS.

WHEN LOAD WAS BEING SECURED THE TIE DOWNS WERE NOT SECURED COMPLETELY. WHILE TRAVELING ON THE ROADWAY THE LOAD SLIPPED CAUSING THE TIE DOWNS TO COME UNDONE AND TWO CONTAINERS TURNED OVER SPILLING MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR.  THE DRIVER STOPPED TO CHECK THE LOAD AND DISCOVERED THE SPILL.  HE PROCEEDED TO UPRIGHT THE CONTAINERS STOPPING THE FLOW, THEN PROCEEDED TO USE ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN UP THE MATERIAL IN THE CARGO AREA OF THE TRUCK.  NO MATERIAL REACHED THE GROUND.

THIS CTN FELL OFF THE TOP OF THIS PLT WHILE IN TRANSIT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THIS WAS NOT SHRINKWRAPPED, AND I FEEL THIS MAY HAVE BEEN STACKED TOO HIGH SO THIS CTN FELL. DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTICED THAT CTN WAS ON THE FLOOR OF TRAILER SO HE PUT THE BOX UPRIGHT.  THE TOP OF CTN WAS WET FROM THIS MATERIAL..CONS. REFUSED THIS CTN SO CTN WAS BROUGHT TO OUR DOCK.. THE CONTAINER LEAKED ONTO OUR DOCK AND THIS MATERIAL WAS USED TO CLEAN UP THE DOCK. THE OTHER 2 CONTAINERS WERE SENT TO OUR SALV STORE. CLAIRE SAAVERDRA

column168: TANK WAS FOUND ON EAST YARD TRACK #43 BY F.R.A. INSPECTORS TO BE LEAKING FROM RUPTURED DISK. CHEM TRAK WAS CALLED, WHO NOTIFIED SHIPPER WHO, IN TURN, SENT UTLX MOBIL REPAIR UNIT FROM WHITING, IN TO REPLACE RUPTURED DISK.
SPILL CAUSED BY OVERFILLING TANK; FOUND OIL OUTSIDE OF HOUSE WERE DRIVER PUT DOWN SPEEDY DRY AND ALSO OIL IN BASEMENT PER SERVICE DEPT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Burst or Ruptured
column168: WHEN LOADING FROM 4 WHEEL FLOAT THE DOCKMAN SLID IT OFF THE SIDE OF THE FLOAT AND BOTTOM METAL PART OF THE DRUM CAME APART FROM THE CARDBOARD SIDES. THIS CAUSED THE LINER TO RUPTURE AND GRANULAR MATERIAL TO SPILL ONTO THE FLOOR.  THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION.

DOCK MAN WAS UNLOADING TRAILER WHEN CARTON FELL OFF A SKID AND HIT THE FLOOR.  IMPACT CAUSED THREE GLASS BOTTLES TO BREAK AT THE BOTTOM RELEASING LIQUID CONTAINED WITHIN.  DAMAGED CARTON WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. DOCK PERSONNEL MUST BE CAREFUL WHEN HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPMENTS TO HANDLE IN SUCH A WAY AS TO PREVENT DAMAGE TO PRODUCT. RECOMMEND THAT BOTTLES BE MADE OF PLASTIC INSTEAD OF GLASS TO PREVENT DAMAGE FROM IMPACT WITH FLOOR.

LOCAL DRIVER DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED CARTON AS HE WAS ABOUT TO DELIVER THE FREIGHT TO THE CUSTOMER.  FREIGHT WAS REFUSED BY CUSTOMER AS UNABLE TO SELL.  CARTON WAS BROUGHT TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. INSPECTION OF THE CARTON REVEALED THAT ONLY ELEVEN OF THE TWELVE BOTTLES WERE IN THE CARTON.  EVIDENTLY THE DAMAGED BOTTLE WAS DISPOSED OF SO THAT CAUSE OF THE DAMAGE IS NOT POSSIBLE TO DETERMINE.

DRUM RECEIVED LEAKING AT LOUISVILLE OFF UNIT 285516 FROM SOUTH HOLLAND. DRUM WAS TRAPPED AND ISOLATED, ORIGIN WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION. APPEARED THE DRUM HAD BEEN HIT BY ANOTHER PALLET ON THE TRAILER CAUSING A SMALL PUNCTURE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.

DOCK MAN DISCOVERED LEAKING PAIL WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER.  THE PAIL HAD BEEN CRIMPED AROUND THE BOTTOM CHIME DUE TO BEING STRUCK BY OTHER FREIGHT. PAIL WAS TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. DOCK PERSONNEL SHOULD LOAD FREIGHT ON TRAILERS IN SUCH A WAY AS TO PROTECT IT FROM POSSIBLE DAMAGE FROM OTHER FREIGHT.
FORKLIFT STRUCK LOWER SECTION OF THE DRUM CAUSING THE BOTTOM RIM TO COME UNSEALED.  THE SHIPPER PROVIDED A RECOVERY DRUM FOR PRODUCT TO BE RETURNED TO THEM

ONE CONTAINER UNLOADED WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM A VALVE ON THE BOTTOM OF THE UNIT.  IT WAS LEAKING FROM A FLANGE WHERE THE VALVE WAS BOLTED TO THE CONTAINER.  THE BOLT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK HALTED.  CONTAINER WAS DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE INTA CT.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: 1 BAG TORN WHEN LOADED ONTO DELIVERY UNIT.  TEAR CAUSED BY ANOTHER PALLET RIPPING INTO THE BAG.  BAG WAS RECOOPED AND OFFERED FOR DELIVERY WITH THE CONSIGNEE REFUSING SAID BAG.  MORE ADEQUATE DUNNAGE TO BE USED IN THE FUTURE TO PREVENT LIKE ACCIDENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: THERE ARE TWO TANKS AT THE FIRE STATION.  OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING 8500 GALLONS OF NO LEAD INTO THE 2000 GALLON TANK AND WHEN THAT FILLED UP HE TRANSFERRED TO THE 8000 GALLON TANK, IN THE PROCESS HE SPILLED 2-3 GALLONS OF GAS ON THE CONCRETE PAD.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT PUT DOWN SOME OIL DRY AND IT WAS CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF BY CLIFF BERRY.  NO DAMAGE AND ALL PARTIES INVOLVED WERE SATISFIED.  OUR DRIVER RETURNED WITH 2000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WHICH WOULD NOT FIT, THEY HAD OVER ORDERED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: THE CARTON WAS STRUCK PROBABLY BY OTHER FREIGHT DURING TRANSPORT CAUSING ONE OF CONTAINER TO PUNCTURE.
FITTING CAME LOOSE AFTER PUMPING STARTED.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN PUMP, CONTAINED SPILL, RESECURED FITTING AND CONCLUDED WITHOUT INCIDENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER STATED HE WAS SOUTHBOUND ON US HWY 41 NEAR TRENTON, KY IN FRANKLIN COUNTY WHEN A PICKUP CROSSED THE CENTER LINE INTO HIS LANE.  DRIVER #1 DROVE ONTO THE SHOULDER TO AVOID A COLLISION.  #1 THEN DROPPED OFF THE SHOULDER AND TRAVELED 102' BEFORE STRIKING A CULVERT WHICH CAUSED THE DRIVER TO LOSE CONTROL AND OVERTURN, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 2,500 GALLONS OF USED OIL INTO A DITCH AND A WHEAT FIELD.  EPA WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST IN THE CLEANUP. TO MITIGATE ANY FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE, ALL TRUCKS ARE BEING EQUIPPED WITH SPILL BOOMS, SHOVELS AND OTHER MATERIAL TO HELP CONTAIN ANY SPILLS.

column168: THIS SKID WAS IN THE MIDDLE OF THE DOCK WITH A SKID ON EACH SIDE.  WHEN THE DOCKMAN WAS USING FORKLIFT TO LOAD THE SKID THE BLADES WENT THROUGH THE SKID IN FRONT AND PUNCTURED (1) 5 GALLON PLASTIC PAIL OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WAS APPROX 1/2 GALLON OF THE MATERIAL LOST AND NOBODY ON THE DOCK THAT EVENING REMEMBERED IF THEY COULD HAVE HIT IT OR NOT.  THIS SKID WAS POORLY STACKED, EVEN IF THIS WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED, THE SHIPPER STACKED THE SKID 4 PAILS HIGH WITH A WOODEN SKID ON TOP OF THE PAILS  ALL SHRINK WRAPPED TOGETHER.  IN MY OPINION THIS WAS AN ACCIDENT WAITING TO HAPPEN.  THE SKIDS HAD TO BE BROKEN DOWN SO THIS MERCHANDISE COULD BE LOADED PROPERLY.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING DIESEL TO UGST.  THE 90% FULL EMERGENCY SHUT DOWN VALVE MALFUNCTIONED AND SHUT FLOW OF PRODUCT OFF.  THE SUDDEN STOPPAGE OF FLOW CAUSED HOSE CONNECTION OT DISENGAGE FROM FILL PIPE.  TRANSPORT DRIVERS WERE COUNSELLED WITH ON UNLOADING TECHNIQUES INVOLVING OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICES AND REMAINING AT IMMEDIATE AREA WHILE UNLOADING.

THE TRANSFER HOSE WAS RUPTURED DURING UNLOADING PROCESS.  EPA WAS NOTIFIED.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED & REPLACED.  SOIL IS BEING TESTED NOW & WILL BE DISPOSED OF PER EPA INSTRUCTIONS AFTER THE REQUIRED TESTS ARE COMPLETED.

column168: DOCKWORKER NOTICED LEAKAGE AROUND THE CAP ON ONE DRUM AFTER MOVING IT FOR UNLOADING.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AFTER IDENTIFYING THE MATERIAL.  THE DRUM WAS SEALED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM AND ALL MATERIAL CLEANED UP PER SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS.  THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING FINAL DISPOSITION.

DOCKWORKER DISCOVERED ONE CARTON WET AND STAINED UPON UNLOADING AND FOUND ONE INNER CONTAINER BROKEN, CAUSING THE MATERIAL TO SPILL.  ALL SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARTON AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION.

AFTER UNLOADING APPROXIMATELY 1,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK, THE CARGO TANK'S DISCHARGE HOSE CAME APART FROM CUSTOMER'S FITTING CONNECTION ON STORAGE TANK, RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF SPILLED MATERIAL. ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN CONTAINMENT AREA AND WASHED DOWN AND RECYCLED THROUGH CUSTOMER'S SYSTEM.

THE TRUCK WAS STOPPED AT A CUSTOMERS PLACE OF BUSINESS (OVERHEAD DOOR CO. OF NORFOLK, 1417 MILLER STONE RD, VIRGINIA BEACH, VA 23455).  THE SALES REPRESENTATIVE HAD SERVICED THEIR CIRCULATING PARTS CLEANER AND WAS LIFTING THE DRUM OF WASTE PETROLEUM NAPTHA WHEN THE DRUM FELL FORWARD INTO THE TRUCK BED, THE LID CAME OFF AND THE CONTENTS (APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON SPILLED INTO THE TRUCK BED).  ALL MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED.

column42: COMPOUND, RUST PREVENTING OR COMPOUND, RUST REMOVING
column168: DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT FLOOR WAS DAMP UNDER ONE OF THE TOTES.  DETERMINED THAT VALVE WAS TIGHT, THAT TOTE WAS NOT PUNCTURED AND THAT IT WAS A SMALL DRIPPING LEAK. CALLED CHEMTREX AND THEY CALLED SHIPPER.  SHIPPER ADVISED US TO PUT PAIL UNDER LEAK WHILE THEY ARRANGED FOR ENVIROMARK TO TRANSFER CONTENTS OF TOTE TO 55 GALLON PLASTIC DRUMS (3 FULL AND APPROX 30 GAL IN 4TH).  ENVIROMARK NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED UP SPILLED MATERIAL.  GOOD MATERIAL WAS SENT TO DESTINATION.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: LOADED SUPERSACKS OF PIT SLUDGE ON 3-5-92.  AT TIME OF LOADING DRIVER NOTICED MOISTURE IN SACKS.  DRIVER SILICONED END GATE AT EDGES TO PREVENT MOISTURE LEAKAGE.  UPON ARRIVING AT HWR FACILITY DRIVER WAS DETAINED DUE TO WASTE CODE DIFFERENCES.  AFTER A DELAY DRIVER NOTICED A DRIP FROM END GATE.  APPROX 10 GALS OF FLUID WERE RELEASED UPON CONCRETE PARKING AREA. (SEE ATTACHED FOR CLEAN UP ACTIONS).  REVIEWED WITH DRIVER ABOUT LOADING MATERIALS IN DUMP WITH EXCESS WATER IN THEM.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: CONSIGNEE PIPELINE RESTRICTED BUT NOT BLOCKED BY FROZEN AND/OR DRIED SALTS OF PRODUCT IN CONSIGNEE UNLOAD PIPELINE.  DRIVER BEGAN UNLOAD, OVER 200 GALLONS WENT INTO CUSTOMER TANK BUT SLOWLY, AND FINALLY STOPPED AS PIPELINE BECAME COMPLETELY BLOCKED.  DRIVER THEN STOPPED UNLOAD, TURNED OFF AIR PRESSURE.  TRUCK PARKED (IN ONLY POSSIBLE POSITION FOR THIS UNLOAD) ON INCLINE AND PRODUCT PARTIALLY COVERED RUPTURE DISC FLANGE OPENING ON TOP OF CARGO TANK AND PLUGGED AIR LINE WHEN CONSIGNEE DISCHARGE LINE BLOCKED. DRIVER WAS HEATING CARGO TANK AIR LINES TO ELIMINATE BLOCKAGE WHILE CONSIGNEE ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THEIR UNLOAD LINE.  TRAILER WAS NOT HOOKED UP TO CONSIGNEE LINE AND AIR WAS OFF.  RUPTURE DISC RUPTURED AND SEVERAL GALLONS OF CAUSTIC SPRAYED UP THRU RUPTURE DISC/FLANGE ON TOP OF THE CARGO TANK AND CAME DOWN ON THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK, THE SIDE OF CONSIGNEE BUILDING, THE CINDER AN CONCRETE UNLOAD AREA AND THE CONCRETE DRIVE/STREET EDGE, ABOUT 30' X 30' AREA.  THE CAUSTIC FROZE IMMEDIATELY, REMAINING IN PLACE AS SALT SPOTS OF WHICH THE NOTICEABLE ONES WERE LATER WASHED DOWN WITH WATER THRU A GARDEN HOSE.  FOR THE FUTURE: CONSIGNEE RBW CHANGED UNLOAD LINE 3/13/92 AND DELIVERY COMPLETED 3/13/92 WITHOUT INCIDENT.

TANK CAR REPORTED LEAKING FROM TOP DURING CAR MOVEMENT.  SHIPPER HIRED FRIT RAILCAR REPAIR TO RESPOND AND MAKE REPAIRS.  RELEASE DUE TO DEFECTIVE VACUUM VENT VALVE AND WORN EDUCTION PIPE FLANGE GASKET.  FRIT REPAIRED BOTH PROBLEMS.  TANKCAR CONTINUED TO DESTINATION.

column168: CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET.  OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED BY AAR-BOE INSPECTOR.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: THE CARGO TANK WAS BACKED INTO AN UNLOADING AREA THAT WAS RECESSED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO THE TRAILER FOR UNLOADING. WHEN THE PRESSURE WAS APPLIED, PRODUCT STARTED SPILLING OUT OF THE DOME AREA AND A CLEAN OUT CAP.  PRODUCT WENT INTO A CONTAINED AREA MADE OF CONCRETE.  THE TRAILER SHOULD BE PRESSURED UP WHILE IT IS ON LEVEL GROUND. IF A LEAK IS DETECTED IT WOULD ONLY BE VAPOR AND NOT LIQUID.  THAT IS IF THE DOME AREA OR CLEAN OUT CAP ARE LOOSE.

column42: ORGANIC PHOSPHATE, ORGANIC PHOSPHATE COMPOUND, OR ORGANIC PHOSPHORUS COMPOUND; SOLID OR DRY
column168: AFTER THE ORIGINAL TRAILER WAS EMPTIED, IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE RESIDUE FROM THIS SHIPMENT, ENOUGH TO BELIEVE THAT WE HAD A SPILL.  WE ISOLATED THE TRAILER AND SECURED IT UNTIL CLEAN UP CREWS WERE BROUGHT IN. column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TO DELIVER A LOAD OF 4,400 GALLONS OF ALUMINUM SULFATE TO THE LAKE LINGANORE WATER TREATMENT PLANT IN FREDERICK COUNTY MARYLAND, A COUNTY FACILITY.  HE INSTEAD DELIVERED IT TO THE CITY OF FREDERICK - LINGANORE FILTRATION PLANT WHICH IS LOCATED SEVERAL MILES FROM THE LAKE LINGANORE FACILITY AND IS OFF LINGANORE ROAD. BOTH FACILITIES ARE OUR CUSTOMERS. HE ARRIVED AT THE PLANT AT 5:00 A.AM AND INFORMED THE PLANT PERSONNEL THAT HE WAS THERE WITH A DELIVERY. THEY WERE NOT EXPECTING HIM, BUT DIRECTED HIM TO WHERE HE SHOULD HOOKUP TO UNLOAD. THE STORAGE TANK IS LOCATED INSIDE A BUILDING AND THE FILL LINE RUNS OUT THROUGH THE WALL TO THE OUTSIDE. THEIR STORAGE TANK HAS A CAPACITY OF 7,000 GALLONS, THEY HAD APPROXIMATELY 5,400 GALLONS IN THE TANK. THEY DID NOT TELL THE DRIVER THIS, THE DRIVER STARTED UNLOADING, SOMETIME LATER PLANT EMPLOYEES NOTIFIED THE DRIVER THAT THE STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFLOWING. HE STOPPED UNLOADING AT THIS POINT. ----------------------- WHEN THE STORAGE TANK REACHED CAPACITY THE ALUMINUM SULFATE WAS FORCED UP THROUGH A LINE TO A 500 GALLON DAY TANK, THIS TANK FILLED AND OVERFLOWED INTO A DIKED AREA WHICH OVERFLOWED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE PLANT AND INTO A SUMP WHICH PUMPED IT TO THEIR SLUDGE POND. THE SLUDGE POND IS WHERE THE ALUMINUM SULFATE WAS TO BE USED SO NO DAMAGE WAS DONE. HOWEVER, SOME OF THE ALUMINUM SULFATE WAS FORCED UP THROUGH THE TANK VENT LINE TO A POINT OUTSIDE THE BUILDING ONTO THE GROUND. I ESTIMATE THAT BETWEEN 150 - 200 GALLONS REACHED THE GROUND. THERE IS A GREAT DEAL OF CONSTRUCTION GOING ON AROUND THE PLANT SO THERE IS NO GRASS OR PLANT LIFE IN THE AREA OF THE SPILL. ------------------------ THE AREA WAS MUDDY FROM MELTING SNOW AND WATER USED BY THE PLANT EMPLOYEES TO DILUTE THE SPILL. THERE APPEARS TO BE NO HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND NO WATER WAYS WERE AFFECTED. ------------- IN THE FUTURE OUR DRIVERS WILL DOUBLE CHECK THEIR PAPERWORK TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE IN THE RIGHT LOCATION AND ALSO HAVE EMPLOYEES AT THE DELIVERY SITE CHECK THE LEVEL IN THEIR TANK TO INSURE THAT THERE IS SUFFICIENT ROOM TO HOLD THE LOAD.

column168: INCIDENT OCCURRED DURING A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO A MOBIL SERVICE STATION LOCATED AT 3650 HWY 6 IN SUGAR LAND, TX.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE DELIVERY ELBOW TO THE FITTING ON THE STATION'S UNLEADED UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. (DELIVERY ELBOW IS AT THE END OF THE DELIVERY HOSE).  THIS CAUSED A SPILL OF APPROX 50 GALS WHICH FLOWED INTO THE ADJOINING SHOPPING CENTER PARKING LOT DRAINAGE SYSTEM AND EVENTUALLY INTO AN OPEN DRAINAGE DITCH.  THE SUGAR LAND FIRE DEPT FLUSHED THE DRAINAGE SYSTEM WITH DISPERANT AND WATER.  THE PRODUCT WAS PUSHED INTO THE OPEN DITCH WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED WITH BOOMS AND VACUUMED UP.  IT WAS TRANSPORTED BY MALONE TRUCKING TO THE MALONE SERVICE CO FACILITY LOCATED AT 5300 CAMPBELL BAYOU RD., TEXAS CITY, TX.  THE MAJORITY OF THE LIQUID VACUUMED UP WAS WATER FROM THE OPEN DRAINAGE DITCH.

DRIVER OF VEHICLE STATED THAT HE WAS TRAVELING IN THE LEFT LANE ON I-85 SOUTH WHEN ANOTHER VEHICLE PASSED HIM ON THE RIGHT AND ABRUPTLY CUT IN FRONT OF HIM.  OUR DRIVER STATED THAT HE SWERVED TO THE LEFT TO AVOID THE OTHER VEHICLE AND THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TANK-TRAILER STRUCK A BRIDGE PILLAR, RIPPING OPEN THE SIDE OF THE TANK, AND SPILLING THE CARGO ON TO THE MEDIAN STRIP.  THE OTHER VEHICLE DID NOT STOP.  INVESTIGATION BY THE CARRIER REVEALED THAT THE DRIVER WAS DRIVING BEYOND THE 10 HOUR RULE WITHOUT 8 HOURS OFF AND HE HAD BEEN ON-DUTY FOR MORE THAT 15 HOURS WITHOUT 8 HOURS OFF DUTY.  DESPITE THE DRIVERS STATEMENTS THE CARRIER FEELS THAT IT IS PROBABLE THAT THE DRIVER DOZED OFF PRIOR TO LEAVING THE HIGHWAY AND STRIKING THE PILLAR.  THERE WERE NO FATALITIES OR INJURIES.  THE FIRM OF FOUR SEASONS INDUSTRIAL SERVICES INC. OF GREENSBORO, NC WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL FROM THE SPILL WAS TRANSPORTED TO LAIDLAW ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES INC IN REIDSVILLE, NC FOR DISPOSAL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO CHARLESTON, SOUTH CAROLINA TO MAKE A DELIVERY OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE.  THE DRIVER WAS IN AN ACCIDENT WHERE HE LEFT THE ROAD ON THE RIGHT HAND SIDE, HIT A SET OF GUARDRAILS, LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE AND ROLLED THE TANKER ON ITS SIDE.  HE THEN SLID INTO ANOTHER SET OF GUARDRAILS, CONTINUED TO SLIDE, HITTING THREE TREES AND COMING TO REST ON A TREE.  A BRANCH FROM THE TREE BROKE A FITTING ON THE TOP OF THE TANKER, RELEASING THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE. THERE IS NO INDICATION OF MECHANICAL FAILURES BY THE TANKER, TRACTOR OR VALVE.  THE TANKER SLID APPROXIMATELY 291 FEET ON IT'S SIDE THROUGH TREES. THE "ROLL GUARD" PROTECTED THE OTHER VALVES ON THE TOP, BUT ONE BRANCH CAME IN AT AN ANGLE AND CRACKED THE VALVE.  THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL FAILURE IN THIS INCIDENT. THE PREVENTION WOULD HAVE TO BE ON THE HUMAN SIDE. WE WERE UNABLE TO NEUTRALIZE THE PRODUCT SPILLED DUE TO HEAVY RAIN, WHICH DILUTED THE PRODUCT

THE TOTE TANK CAME INTO COLUMBUS TERMINAL ON TRAILER 15-8743 FROM CINCINNATI.  THE TANK WAS LEAKING AROUND SEAL OF TANK.  WE CALLED SHIPPER AND TALKED TO DICK WOLF WITH DIVERSEY/DUBOIS.  HE ASKED US TO SEND THE LEAKING TOTE TANK BACK TO THEM.
**NO REMARKS**

PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING FROM A CLEAN OUT CAP ON THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK.  DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THE SMALL LEAK UNTIL ARRIVING AT THE CONSIGNEE TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT.  CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE CAUSED BY THE CLEAN OUT CAP BEING CROSS-THREADED WHEN IT WAS LAST INSTALLED.  BEING CROSS-THREADED PREVENTED A TIGHT SEAL ON THE GASKET BETWEEN THE CAP AND THE TANK. IT IS NOT BELIEVED THAT ANY OF THE PRODUCT MADE CONTACT WITH THE GROUND WHILE EN ROUTE BECAUSE OF THE SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN LOST AND THE SMALL SIZE OF PRODUCT STAIN LEFT ON THE TRAILER IN THE AREA OF THE CLEAN OUT CAP. CLEAN OUT CAP WAS PROPERLY INSTALLED PRIOR TO ANY FURTHER USE OF THE CARGO TANK.

column168: TRACTOR AND TRAILER TRAVELING WESTBOUND U.S. 52 NEAR FRANKLIN FURNACE, SCIOTO COUNTY, OHIO.  DRIVER FELL ASLEEP, UNIT LEFT THE HIGHWAY, GOING TO THE RIGHT, DOWN AN EMBANKEMENT.  HIT CONCRETE CULVERT WITH RIGHT SIDE WHEELS, CAUSING UNIT TO TURN OVER, LANDING ON IT'S TOP.  DRIVER WEARING SEAT BELT, WAS SUSPENDED UPSIDE DOWN, UNTIL FIREMEN AND EMT REMOVED HIM FROM TRACTOR.  SUSTAINED BROKEN ARM AND LACERTATIONS, SPENT ONE NIGHT IN HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  PUMPED PRODUCT OFF INTO ANOTHER TRAILER.  ACTUAL LOSS OF PRODUCT WAS ABOUT 13 GALLONS.  THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER IN THE DITCH LINE.  UNDERFLO DAMS WERE CONSTRUCTED AND SORBENT PADS WERE USED TO PICKUP SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.

CHEMIST NOTICED LIQUID WASTE ON PASSENGER SIDE OF TRUCK AFTER TRUCK WAS PARKED AT BAY DOOR.  THEY HAD WALKED AROUND TO GET THEIR EQUIPMENT AND TO DO A POST-TRIP OF THE TRUCK.  AFTER NOTICING THE LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE TRUCK AND DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TRUCK, A CALL WAS PUT IN TO THE OPERATIONS MANAGER, JACKIE NOLES. THE TRUCK WAS MOVED TO AN UNLOADING DOCK.  OIL DRI WAS PUT DOWN ON THE INITIAL PAVEMENT SPILL AND CLEANED UP.  OIL DRI WAS PUT DOWN ON FLOOR TO STOP AND CONTAIN LEAKAGE ON FLOOR OF TRUCK.  TRUCK WAS THEN OFFLOADED TO GET TO LEAKING DRUM.  LEAKING DRUM WAS OVERPACKED; FLOOR OF TRUCK WAS CLEANED UP; AND ALL CONTAMINATED OIL DRI WAS PUT IN SAME OVERPACK THAT LEAKING DRUM WAS IN.  THE NEXT MORNING, THE SPILLAGE ON SIDE OF TRUCK WAS CLEANED OFF.

BARTON SOLVENTS, INC.'S TRACTOR/TRAILER PULLED UNDER THE LOADING RACK AT LAKE RIVER TERMINAL IN BERWYN, IL TO LOAD 600 GALLONS OF DIACETONE ALCOHOL IN A 1,000 GALLON COMPARTMENT.  AS A LAKE RIVER TERMINAL EMPLOYEE STARTED TO LOAD THE TRAILER, THE PUMP QUIT.  AN ELECTRICIAN WAS CALLED TO REPAIR THE PUMP BUT HE STARTED FOLLOWING ON IT BEFORE THE PUMP WAS SHUT OFF. WHEN THE PUMP WAS REPAIRED, MATERIAL STARTED FLOWING AGAIN AND OVERFILLING THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 260 GALLONS WERE SPILLED ON THE GROUND.  ONCE THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED, THE PUMP WAS SHUT OFF, AND THE DIACETONE WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  LAKE RIVER TERMINAL TAKES FULL RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE SPILL, CLEANUP, AND DISPOSAL.  WE RECOMMEND THAT LAKE RIVER IMPROVE THEIR PROCEDURES FOR A LOCK-OUT AND TAG-OUT SYSTEM FOR LOADING TRANSPORTS.

TRAILER HAD BEEN WASHED OUT AND VALVES LEFT OPEN TO PREVENT FREEZING. TRAILER WAS PARTIALLY LOADED FROM TOP AT ONE FILL STATION.  TRAILER WAS MOVED TO SECOND FILLING STATION TO COMPLETE LOAD.  OUTLET CAP REMOVED AND CAUSTIC ESCAPED SPLASHING AGAINST LOADERS RUBBER APRON AND UNDER HIS FACE SHIELD.  VALVE WAS TURNED OFF IMMEDIATELY AND EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO HOSPITAL.  RELEASED AND RETURNED TO WORK.  VALVES ARE NOW TAGGED IF LEFT OPEN TO ALERT FILLERS.  ALSO, PRIOR TO FILLING, ALL VALVES ARE TO BE CHECKED TO MAKE SURE THEY ARE CLOSED.  CAUSTIC SODA RELEASED WAS NEUTRALIZED USING SODIUM BISULFITE AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY THROUGH BRANCH ELEMENTARY NEUTRALIZATION SYSTEM.

A TOTAL POWER FAILURE AT THE SAN DIEGO AIRPORT RENDERED THE NORMAL LOADING/UNLOADING OPERATION USELESS.  BECAUSE OF THIS SHUTDOWN, AMERICAN AIRLINES REQUESTED HELP IN FUELING THEIR PLANES. ARCO DRIVER WAS UNLOADING FROM TRUCK/TRAILER THRU "DEFUELING" LINE DIRECTLY TO LOADING MOTOR INTO REFUELING TRUCK (AMERICAN). WHEN ARCO DRIVER WAS CHANGING OFFLOADING HOSE FROM ONE COMPARTMENT TO THE OTHER, THE AMERICAN REFUELING DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE SUCTION CREATING BACK PRESSURE ON LINE, THUS CAUSING 5 GALLONS OF JET-A TO SPILL INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.  AREA WAS CLEANED WITH SORBENT MATERIAL AND PROPERLY DISPOSED FO ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE. THIS WAS FREAK OCCURRANCE UNDER EMERGENCY CONDITIONS AND COULD NOT HAVE BEEN FORESEEN.  A PROCEDURE WILL BE DEVELOPED TO ADDRESS THIS TYPE OF OFFLOADING/LOADING.

CARGO TANK WAS FINISHED LOADING, DRIVER WAS WALKING HOSE, HOLDING OPEN END UP, TOWARD THE LOADING VALVE, WITH THE INTENTION OF DRAINING ANY RESIDUAL LIQUID INTO A 5 GALLON BUCKET, WHICH WOULE BE DEPOSITED INTO THE TANK. (ONCE ALL LIQUID WAS ACCUMULATED NEAR THE VALVE, THE HOSE WOULD THEN BE DISCONECTED FROM CARGO TANK; NORMALLY, THIS ACCUMULATION WOULD NOT AMOUNT TO MORE THAN ONE OR TWO GALLONS, AS THE PRODUCT PUMP IS CAPABLE OF DRAINING MOST OF THE LIQUID WHILE LOADING).  AS THE DRIVER WAS WALKING THE HOSE TOWARD THE VALVE, HE MOMENTARILY LOST GRIP OF THE HOSE, WHICH CAUSED THE LIQUID TO FLOW TOWARD THE OPEN END, RESULTING IN A ONE GALLON SPILL ONTO THE TANKER PAD AREA.  SPECIAL VALVE FITTINGS HAVE BEEN ORDERED WHICH WILL HAVE A DRAIN VALVE BUILT INTO THEM, WHICH SHOULD REDUCE THE AWKWARDNESS OF THE FINAL STEPS DURING LOADING WITH THE PRODUCT PUMP.

MEDLER, THAT TANK CAR TILX 100168 WAS OBSERVED TO HAVE PRODUCT SPEWING FROM THE TOP WHILE BEING SWITCHED.  THE SWITCHMAN, J. MARVES, HAD PRODUCT SPLASH ON HIM AND WAS TAKEN TO ST. FRANCES CABRINI HOSPITAL, RECEIVED FIRST AID TREATMENT AND WAS RELEASED (LOST 1 WORK DAY). CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SSA/HM ROBINSON RESPONDED. SSA/HM ROBINSON'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK WAS DUE TO A FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE COVER/SPLASH CAP OF THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY HAD NOT BEEN PINNED AND HAD PIVOTED OPEN AND THE ATTACHEMENT CHAIN FOR THE COVER CAP WAS PARTIALLY CORRODED TO THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY BODY.  FAILED FRANGIBLE DISC (BS&B,100 PSI) WAS REPLACED WITH NEW DISC OF LIKE KIND. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, CHEMTREC AND MR. JOSEPH SHERIDAN, GENERAL MANAGER FOR PHELPS DODGE CORP.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: I RECEIVED A CALL FROM MY DRIVER (HARRY BUCHHORN) SAYING HE HAD A SPILL. YOU HAVE TO DOUBLE-PARK ON THE STREET, FACING UPHILL, TO MAKE THIS DELIVERY.  THE TANK IS AN UNDERGROUND TANK IN THE SIDEWALK.  IT HAD A DOWNSPOUT THAT IS PORTABLE.  THE CUSTOMER INSERTS THIS INTO THE TANK AND TIES IT DOWN.  THE CUSTOMER DOES HAVE A TANK METERING DEVICE.  TRUCK WAS SET UP AND AFTER CUSTOMER SIGNED PAPERWORK STATING THAT HOSE CONNECTIONS ARE PROPER AND SUFFICIENT SPACE IS AVAILABLE FOR DELIVERY, THE TRUCK STARTED PUMPING OFF.  THE CUSTOMER ORDERED 6000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  WHEN THE TRUCK WAS ALMOST EMPTY, THE DRIVER STARTED TO WALK HIS HOSE TO THE TRUCK PUMP.  IT WAS AT THAT POINT THAT HE NOTICED IT COMING UP FROM THE DOWNSPOUT AND OUT OF THE VENT.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND CLOSED HIS VALVE.  HE GRABBED SOME TOWELS THAT HE HAD IN THE TRAILER AND THREW THEM IN THE GUTTER TO CONTAIN THE SPILL.  HE THEN NOTIFIED THE FOREMAN AND RECEIVING CLERK.  THE RECEIVING CLERK SHOVED A HOSE THROUGH THE WINDOW AND BEGAN HOSING DOWN THE AREA.  LESS THAN TEN (10) GALLONS WAS SPILLED AND MAYBE FOUR OR FIVE GALLONS WAS HOSED INTO THE SEWER DRAIN.

column168: **PER GARY GRAVES - 5/20/92 - ADVISED THAT CHEMICAL SPILLED WAS MIXTURE OF 3 COMMODITIES LISTED IN ITEM 12.  "BONDING AGENT" SB CLASSIFIED AS FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS.  SEE ATTACHMENTS.** CHARTER FLIGHT 511 WAS ENROUTE TO SANTO DOMINGO FROM NEW YORK AND CREW MEMBERS NOTICED A UNUSUAL ODOR IN THE COCKPIT.  THEY ADVISED CVG FLIGHT CONTROL THAT THEY WERE NOT DECLARING AN EMERGENCY BUT THE ODOR WAS NOTICEABLE.  THEY REQUESTED TO DIVERT TO MIA AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE.  OUR MIA LOCATION WAS NOTIFIED TO SEND PERSONNEL TO THE AIRPORT TO HELP IDENTIFY OR HELP IN THE SITUATION.  ALL UNLOAD AND IDENTIFICATION OF THE INVOLVED SHIPMENTS WERE HANDLED BY MIAMI AIRCRAFT SUPPORT, THE CONTRACTED DHL GROUND HANDLER IN THE MIA FACILITY.  THE QUESTIONABLE SHIPMENTS WERE LOCATED IN POSITION #1 OF THE AIRCRAFT.  THEY WERE PULLED OFF THE AIRCRAFT AND TENDERED TO ANTILLAS AIR AGENT IN THE MIA AREA WHICH IS: DAE BONG DOMINICAN CORP 15098 SW 135TH PLACE SUNRISE, FL  33326 ONLY ONE CONTAINER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AND DEFECTIVE WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE OF THE INTERIOR CONTENTS.  ALL PAPER WORK AVAILABLE IS ATTACHED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: JACK GRAY TRANSPORT, INC.'S TRUCK NUMBER 808, DRIVEN BY LES TOWNSELL, PULLED INTO T.A. TRUCK STOPS OF AMERICA, EXIT 77, HIGHWAY 59 & 20, TUSCALOOSA, AL.  ALABAMA STATE POLICE INFORMED HIM THAT THE VEHICLE WAS LEAKING LIQUID. LES FOUND THAT THE TAILGATE WAS LEAKING.  MR. TOWNSELL LOADED A FROZEN LOAD OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WITH PCB'S, RQ HAZARDOUS WASTE SOLID, NOS ORM-E NA 9188 OUT OF NATIONAL SOUTHWIRE, HAWSVILLE, KY AND WAS HEADED TO CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC., EMELLE, AL.  THE LOAD HAD STARTED TO THAW CAUSING LIQUID TO SEEP FROM THE TAILGATE. THE STATE BROUGHT IN SAND TO PUT ON THE GROUND WHERE THE LIQUID FROM THE TRUCK WAS DRIPPING.  ADEM WAS ALSO AT THE SCENE.  CHEMICAL WASTE SENT OUT OF A CREW OF TWO, PLUS SUPLIES TO REPAIR THE TAILGATE SO THAT THE LOAD COULD BE TAKEN ON TO THE LANDFILL.  CHEMICAL WASTE CLEANED UP THE AREA AND PUT ABOUT 1000 LBS. OF CONTAMINATED SAND INTO THE LOAD. THE LOAD WENT ON TO THE LANDFILL WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEM.
column172: Highway hopper trailer for solid materials only

column168: 0805-FREIGHT WAS ACCIDENTALLY BUMPED OFF ONE OF OUR CONVEYOR BELTS, FELL TO THE FLOOR (A DISTANCE OF ABOUT 2 1/2 FEET) AND BROKE. 0815-ZORBITE, AN OIL SPILL ABSORBANT WAS PLACED ON THE SPILLED LIQUID AND THE FREIGHT WAS REMOVED FROM THE DOCK AND PLACED OUTSIDE BY AN EMPLOYEE WEARING SAFETY CLOTHES. 0835-AIRBORNE HAZMAT WAS CALLED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. 0907-ALDRICH CHEMICAL CO CALLED TO CONFIRM THAT A HAZMAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO OUR LOCATION TO REMOVE THE DAMAGED FREIGHT. 1440-HAZMAT TEAM REMOVED THE DAMAGED FREIGHT AND CLEANED ALL REMNANTS OF THE SPILL. OUT FEELING IS THAT THE FREIGHT WAS IMPROPERLY PACKAGED.  A FALL OF 2 1/2 FEET SHOULD NOT HAVE RESULTED IN BREAKAGE.  THE PACKAGE COULD NOT BE CAREFULLY EXAMINED DUE TO ITS HAZARDOUS NATURE AND THE EXTENT OF DAMAGE TO THE PACKAGE CAUSED BY THE LIQUID.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 03/02/92 @10:00 AM JOHN BUNNER, RIDGELEY, WV, CONTACTED LARRY J. BROCK, PRESIDENT, BROCK STEEL CO., IN. IN REFERENCE TO BROCK STEEL CO. REMOVING A SCRAP CARGO TANK FROM THE PROPERTY OF GARLAND PETROLEUM CO., 12 E ROBERT'S STREET, CUMBERLAND, MD.  THE CARGO TANK WAS ORIGINALLY OWNED BY GARLAND PET. CO AND HAD NOT BEEN USED FOR APPROXIMATELY 10-15 YEARS.  GARLAND PETROLEUN CO. ADVISED THAT THEY GAVE THE CARGO TANK TO JOHN BUNNER.  LARRY J. BROCK ADVISED MR. BUNNER THAT HE WOULD REMOVE THE TANK BUT THAT THE TANK HAD TO BE EMPTY AND CLEAN.  BROCK STEEL CO., EDWARD P.M. LEASE, DRIVER, AS INSTRUCTED TO PICK UP THE EMPTY TANK AND BRING IT TO THE BROCK STEEL CO. FOR DISPOSAL, (APPROX 1/2 MILE).  MR. LEASE PROCEEDED TO 12 ROBERT'S STREET AND MET MR. JOHN BUNNER.  MR. LEASE CRAWLED UP ON TOP OF THE TANK AND LOOKED IN THE "MIDDLE HOLE".  HE STATED THAT THE OTHER TWO DOORS WOULD NOT OPEN.  MR. BUNNER TOLD HIM THAT EVERYTHING WAS "OK" AND THAT THE VALVES ON THE TANK WERE SECURE.  MR. LEASE HOOKED HIS TRACTOR UP TO THE TANK AND PROCEEDED BACK TO BROCK STEEL CO.  MR. LEASE WAS FOLLOWED CLOSELY BACK UP THE STREET BY MR. BUNNER.  APPARENTLY THE VALVES ON THE TANK LET GO WHEN MR. LEASE PULLED ONTO LAFAYETTE STREET AND LIQUID WAS SPILLING OUT.  MR. BUNNER DID NOT SIGNAL MR. LEASE THAT THERE WAS A PROBLEM AT ALL DURING THE 1/2 MILE TO BROCK STEEL CO.  MR. LEASE STATED THAT HE THOUGHT THAT WATER WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANK.  HE FELT THAT MR. BUNNER WOULD HAVE SIGNALLED HIM IF THERE WAS A PROBLEM. PREVENTION: ALL DRIVERS MUST MAKE SURE THAT ALL/ANY CLOSED CONTAINERS ARE EMPTY AND CLEAN.  "DONT'T MOVE IT UNLESS SAFE TO DO SO".  IT IS THE DRIVER'S RESPONSIBILITY TO MAKE SURE ANY/ALL TANKS ARE EMPTY BEFORE HOOKING UP TO THEM.

column168: MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MYO MAURICE MITCHEL THAT SWITCH CREWS REPORTED A STRONG ODOR NEAR CAR GATX 98371.  DUE TO THE FACT MANAGER STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, INSPECTOR A.D. MATY RESPONDED.  INSEPCTOR MATY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LEAK FROM THE TANK, BOTTOM OUTLET, CLOSED LOADING/UNLOADING SYSTEM OR MANHOLE COVER.  TANK WAS EQUIPPED WITH AN MGM MODEL #175 SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  DEVICE WAS NOTED TO HAVE THE CONTROL VALVE LOOSE ON THE GAUGING TUBE, NO PLUG IN THE DISCHARGE PORT AND HEAVY ACCUMULATION OF MATERIAL THAT APPEARED TO BE DRIED RESIDUE, INCLUDING SOME DAMPNESS. INSPECTOR MATY REMOVED SLIP TUBE CONTROL VALVE AND GAUGING DEVICE POINTER CAGE TO GAIN ACCESS TO THE PACKING.  RESIDUE OF ACID WAS WASHED OFF AND TWO TEFLON PACKING RINGS WERE INSTALLED.  DEVICE WAS REASSEMBLED USING TEFLON TAPE ON THE THREADS AND CONTROL VALVE WAS REAPPLIED WITH A 1/4" PLUG FOR THE DISCHARGE PORT.  INSPECTOR MATY ALSO NOTED EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE NOT FULLY WRENCH TIGHT.  MR. BILL GASSON OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED FOR REPORTING PURPOSES ONLY.

column168: AT 0830 3-9-92, DOCKMAN R HOPKINS NOTICED A SMALL WET SPOT ON THE SIDE OF A PALLET CONTAINING 27 CARTONS.  THIS WET SPOT SEEMED TO BE SMOKING.  THIS WAS REPORTED TO THE TERMINAL MANAGER, R COOPER AND THE AREA WAS SECURED AND EMPLOYEES WERE ADVISED OF A POSSIBLE SPILL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED TO OBTAIN AN MSDS SHEET AND FOR CLEAN UP ASSISTANCE.  THE SHIPPER SUGGESTED WE CALL A CLEAN UP TEAM.  J ALEXANDER, SAFETY SUPERVISOR WAS INFORMED AND ECOLOGY & ENVIRONMENT WAS CALLED.  THEY IN TURN CONTACTED SPIL TECH SERVICE OF LITTLE ROCK TO HELP WITH THE SPILL.  SPIL TECH PROVIDED THE CLEAN UP.

AT 0230 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED ON DC-9 A/C 938AX, PARKED AT GATE B-102. UPON ARRIVAL ON SCENE I COULD NOT DETECT AND ODOR.  THIS ODOR WAS LOCATED IN BELLIES 1 AND 2.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0250 THE HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS REQUESTED BACK TO 938AX.  THE UNLOAD CREW FOUND THE PACKAGE THAT WAS GIVING OFF THE ODOR.  IT WAS "COSMETICS, NOS" ID 8005.  THIS WAS PROPERLY MARKED LABELED WITH A CLASS 9 LABEL AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT.  CONTAINED IN THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS 24, 8 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTICLES WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE (FLIP TOP).  THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES THAT LEAKED INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THIS IS "NAIL POLISH REMOVER" IN THE 8 OUNCE PLASTIC RECEPTICLES.

column168: DOCKMAN UNLOADING A TRAILER HAD A PALLET OF FREIGHT ON FORK LIFT.  WHEN PUTTING PALLET ON WAREHOUSE FLOOR THE FORKS WERE PROTRUDING OUT THE FRONT OF THE PALLET AND 1 FORK STRUCK SIDE OF DRUM WHICH WAS ON WAREHOUSE FLOOR. DOCKMAN WAS UNAWARE OF DRUM PUNCTURE UNTIL HE UNLOADED ANOTHER PALLET OF SAME MERCHANDISE WHEN HE SAW LIQUID ON FLOOR.  NE NOTIFIED FOREMAN AND DRUM WAS LAID DOWN ON ITS SIDE AND PLACED ON A SKID.  THE SPILLED CHEMICAL HAD EVAPORATED AND NO RESIDUE WAS LEFT ON FLOOR.  THE DRUM HAD A CRACK APPROX 3/4" LONG IN SIDE  1 1/2" FROM BOTTOM CHIME.  THE CRACK WAS TAPED OVER TO PREVENT EVAPORATION AND CONTAMINATION OF PRODUCT.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AT 0135 HRS 3-18-92 MR JIM LONG AT CHEMTREC ADVISED THAT LOG #13611 WILL APPLY TO THIS INCIDENT.  DRUM PATCHED AND PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER BY DUPONT PERSONNEL.

ADVISED BY GR. RAPIDS - MECHANICAL DEPT THAT CAR ACSX 220101 WAS FOUND LEAKING ACCOUNT OF TANK CORROSION ON THE TOP RIGHT SIDE OF CAR.  CAR AT INDUSTRY AND FOUND BY HAVILAND PERSONNEL.  ALLIED SIG., HAVILAND AND FIRE DEPT STOPPED LEAK.  CAR OFF - LOADED INTO STORAGE TANKS AT FACILITY & 500 LBS OF SODIUM BICARB. USED TO NEUTRALIZE CAR'S RESIDUE.  CSX WAS NOT NOTIFIED OF INCIDENT UNTIL 3-9-92, 1430 HRS. THIS REPORT IS BEING SUBMITTED AS "HAVING KNOWLEDGE OF INCIDENT".  MECH DEPT (CSX) AND HAVILAND PERSONNEL ADVISED OF THE FOLLOWING: 1) CAR MUST BE PLACARDED "RESIDUE" - ACCOUNT CAR HAS NOT BEEN CLEANED AND PURGED. 173.29(A)(C) 2) CAR MUST BE STENCILED ACCORDING TO 174.50(D) LEAKING TANK CARS. 3) HAVILAND OR ALLIED SIG. SHOULD INQUIRE AS TO WHETHER THE CAR MUST MOVE UNDER AN EMERGENCY EXEMPTION - CONTACT POINT SHOULD BE O.H.M.T. - ALAN TABOR (202) 366-9178.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS NOTIFIED THAT CAR TILX 100324 WAS LEAKING AT LLOYD YARD.  SSA/HM REEDER RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY VENT HAD OPENED WHICH ALLOWED ACID TO SPILL ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR.  FURTHER INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A BS&B, 100# STAINLESS STEEL FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE HOUSING HAD TWO GASKETS IN PLACE AND THE DISC SHOWED SIGNS OF CORROSION/DISCOLORATION.  A NEW DISC AND GASKET WERE INSTALLED.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS WERE SECURE AND NO OTHER DEFECTS NOTED.  CHEMTREC AND AMERICAN CYANAMID, MR. VERDA, WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

ALL BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC AND BASF WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) C.L. HILL WAS NOTIFIED BY AGENT RAY SIMS THAT TILX 10015 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT DQ&E INTERCHANGE.  SSA/HM HILL RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT ACID HAD BEEN LEAKING FROM THE FILL HOLE AREA.  REMOVAL OF FILL HOLE COVER DETERMINED THAT THE GASKET HAD NOT BEEN LINED UP WITH THE RIM OF THE FILL HOLE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT WHEN CAR WAS MOVED.  SSA/HM HILL REMOVED OLD GASKET AND REPLACED SAME WITH GORTEX ROPE WHICH SECURED FILL HOLE.  CHEMTREC, JOE MALZZIO AND SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE BILL LUEBBERT WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) G.B. REEDER WAS CONDUCTING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AT LLOYD YARD AND NOTED TANK CAR CELX 2238 HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF ALCOHOL SEEPING OUT FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  SSA/HM REEDER INSPECTION DETERMINED NO APPARENT SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  ALL VALVES WERE CLOSED AND PLUGS IN PLACE AND TIGHT. THE BOLTS HOLDING THE VALVES IN PLACE WERE TIGHTENED SLIGHTLY AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  CHEMTREC AND HOECHST CELANESE, JAN NORRIS WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.A. LOW WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE EAST END SWITCH CREW NOTED SPLASHING COMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 76498.  SSA/HM LOW RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT 15 TO 25 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD HARDENED TO SIDES AND TOP OF CAR.  SWING BOLTS ON MANWAY WERE LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT.  SWING BOLTS WERE SECURED AND BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND MANWAY WERE INSPECTED.  CHEMTREC, JOE MALZZIO AND FRONTIER SUPERVISOR, DAVID SNOW WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.A. LOW WAS NOTIFIED THAT BN 974327 WAS SPLASHING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP DURING SWITCH MOVEMENTS. SSA/HM LOW RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE THREE INCH UNLOADING VALVE FLANGE.  ALL STUDS AND NUTS AROUND FLANGE WERE LOOSE AND LEAKAGE ALSO NOTED FROM SAMPLE TUBE.  SAMPLE TUBE VALVE WAS BROKEN OFF AND MISSING.  SSA/HM LOW REPLACED GASKET ON THREE INCH UNLOADING VALVE AND PLUGGED THE SAMPLE TUBE WHICH STOPPED LEAKS. SEAL UP-C-52382 WAS APPLIED AND MANWAY WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE INTACT SEAL, FRONTIER OIL - 18941. CHEMTREC, JOE MALZZIO AND DAVID SNOW, FRONTIER OIL & REFINING WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED THAT SWITCH CREWS REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA NEAR CAR UTLX 80577. DUE TO THE FACT THAT MANAGER STINE WAS IN OMAHA, NE., A.D. MATY, CHIEF INSPECTOR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES (AAR) AGREED TO RESPOND. INSPECTOR MATY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE "A" END LIQUID EDUCTION BALL VALVE AT THE STEM/BODY PASSAGE.  WHEN THE PACKING GLAND RETAINER SCREWS WERE LOOSENED IN ORDER TO REMOVE THE GLAND TO APPLY ADDITIONAL PACKING, THE LEAKAGE INCREASED CONSIDERABLY.  INSPECTOR MATY RETIGHTENED THE RETAINER SCREWS AND THE LEAKAGE STOPPED.  THE VALVE WAS OPENED AND CLOSED SEVERAL TIMES AND NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS NOTED. MR. JIM LONG OF CHEMTREC AND MR. DON AYERS, TRAFFIC MANAGER AT C.F. INDUSTRIES WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

MARK GLENN OF THE TEXAS RAILROAD COMMISSION WAS INSPECTING CARS AT ANGLETON YARD AND NOTED PLCX 220403 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM DOW CHEMICAL, FREEPORT, TX. WERE PRESENT AND THE OUTLET VALVE SCREWS WERE TIGHTENED.  LEAK WAS RETARDED TO ONE DROP PER MINUTE BUT NOT COMPLETELY PRODUCT RELEASED AND CAR WAS RETURNED TO DOW FOR UNLOADING AND REPAIR.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

SIMPLOT AND IOWA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES, KATHLEEN LEE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

WHITELEY NOTED A MINOR LEAK FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE OF TANK CAR GATX 49216, RESIDUE EMPTY.  DUE TO MINOR NATURE OF LEAK, CAR WAS STENCILED "LEAKY TANK DO NOT LOAD UNTIL REPAIR" AND RELEASED TO DESTINATION. SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.W. ALM WAS NOTIFIED BY MANAGER TRAIN OPERATIONS (MTO), B. MUSIC THAT ELKO LOCAL TRAIN COUPLED TO CAR GATX 64266 AT SIERRA CHEMICAL, BATTLE MOUNTAIN, NV.  CAR HAD BEEN UNLOADED ON THE SIDING AND HOSES AND VALVES HAD BEEN DISCONNECTED FOR THE TRAIN CREW TO MOVE CAR. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: MARCH 11, 1992 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 AM ENVIRCO TRANSPORTATION, INC. UNIT HEADED EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 80 IN PENNSYLVANIA ENROUTE TO THE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY IN PALMERTON, PA., ENCOUNTERED HAZARDOUS DRIVING CONDITIONS WITH SNOW AND HIGH WINDS.  ENTERING A BEND IN THE HIGHWAY SLID OFF THE ROAD ONTO THE LEFT BERM AND IMPACTED WITH A HILLSIDE HIGHWAY DIVIDER.  UPON IMPACT PARTIALLY OVERTURNED RUPTURING THE CONTAINER CAUSING SOME PORTION OF THE CONTENTS TO BE RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND SURFACE.  IMMEDIATELY THE PA. STATE POLICE, PENNDOT, THE PA. DER, OUR CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR B.E.S. AND THE SUGAR VALLEY FIRE DEPT. WERE RESPONDERS AT THE SCENE.  UNDER CLOSE SUPERVISION BY MR. BOB FISHER, PA. DER THE CLEAN UP WAS CONDUCTED IN A TIMELY MANNER AND TO HIS COMPLETE SATISFACTION.  ETI HAS APPLIED FOR ACCEPTANCE FOR THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIAL AT MDI IN DETROIT MICHIGAN.  THIS ACCEPTANCE IS FORTHCOMING AND A COPY OF THE COMPLETED MANIFEST WILL FOLLOW.  ADVERSE WEATHER CONDITIONS AND THE LACK OF SUFFICIENT AREA TO PULL OFF ROADWAY IS THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT.

column168: FREIGHT ARRIVED AT SLC TERMINAL.  ADDITIONAL LABELS WERE THEN STAPLED TO THE THREE BOXES.  THEY EACH WERE ATTACHED WITH FOUR STAPLES.  THE STAPLES WERE THROUGH FIBERBOARD BOX AND PUNCTURED SMALL HOLES IN TWO OF THE THREE PACKAGES.  THE TWO DAMAGED PACKAGED LEAKED APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF ISPARRAFINIC HYDROCARBON.  ALL OF THE CONTENTS THAT LEAKED WAS ABSORBED BY FIBERBOARD BOX AND A PALLET THAT FREIGHT WAS ON. ACTIONS TAKEN:  EMERY PERSONNEL NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF INCIDENT.  SHIPPER PREPARED NEW SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS AND SENT WITH NEW PACKING MATERIALS.  DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS REPACKAGED AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER ON BILL #SLC 525725084-5.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D.W. ALM WAS NOTIFIED THAT KCCX 2406 WAS NOTED HAVING LIQUID ON THE TOP OF THE TANK.  CAR WAS SPOTTED AT THE SIERRA CHEMICAL SIDING IN BATTLE MOUNTAIN, NV.  SSA/HM ALM CONTACTED SIERRA CHEMICAL MANAGER ERIC PROWITZ AND HE RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT.  MANAGER PROWITZ'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE BS&B, 100 PSI, MODEL TX, DISC WAS RUPTURED.  BURST DISC WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A NEW 100 PSI DISC.  CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED BY SIERRA CHEMICAL.

AT 0220 RAMP SUPERVISOR, SCOTT MARTIN, REPORTED A LIQUID ON THE RAMP AT GATE C-41. UPON ARRIVAL ON SCENE, I, TONY FRYE, WENT UP TI THE WOODEN RECEPTICLE TO SEE WHAT THE LIQUID MATERIAL WAS ON THE RAMP. I IDENTIFIED IT AS "MERCURY". THIS CAME OUT OF THE WOODEN RECEPTICLE THAT WAS ON THE RAMP. THE ONLY MARKING ON THE BOX WAS "MAN-O-METER". I REQUESTED ASSISTANCE TO CLEAN UP THE MERCURY AND SEE WHAT WAS CONTAINED IN THE WOODEN RECEPTICLE. FOUND INSIDE THE WOOEN RECEPTICLE WAS AN INSTUMENT THAT WAS FIVE FEET LONG AND HAD A GLASS TUBE THAT RAN THE ENTIRE LENGTH. THIS GLASS TUBE WAS BROKEN. THE GLASS TUBE WAS APPROXIMATELY 12 INCH IN DIAMETER. THRER WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT IN THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE BUILDING DUE TO THE POISON INHALATION HAZARD OF MERCURY.

MATLACK INC, STEVE OSTERHAUT, WAS NOTIFIED FOR TANK TRUCK TO TRANSFER PRODUCT.  TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED 03/24/92 AND ALL RECOVERED PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN THE TANK TRUCK CONTAINER. column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 0330 HOURS, MONDAY, MARCH 30, 1992, WHILE INSPECTING TANK CARS INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT OF CONRAIL TRAIN WPPA-70, TANK CAR NDYX-3102 (LIQUIFIED PETROLEUM GAS) WAS FOUND WITH A SLIGHT LEAK FROM THE THREADS OF THE VAPOR LINE ANGLE VALVE PLUG. RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM HUNTSMAN POLYPROPYLENE (CONSIGNEE) REMOVED THE PLUG AND PLACED TEFLON TAPE ON THE THREADS. PLUG WAS REINSERTED INTO THE VALVE AND TIGHTENED. NO LEAK WAS OBSERVED WHEN THE PLUG THREADS WERE CHECKED WITH SOAPY WATER SOLUTION. CAR REPAIRED AT 0420 HOURS, MARCH 30, 1992. THE SOUTH TRUCKS (WHEELS) OF TANK CAR NDYX-31025 WERE DERAILED AND CARS WAS UPRIGHT AND INLINE ON THE TRACKS. THIS LEAK IS NOT CONSIDERED TO HAVE OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT, BUT DUE TO A PREVIOUS VALVE DEFECT. TRAIN WPAA-70 DERAILED CARS SOUTH ON THE SHELL INDUSTRIAL TRACK IN W. DEPTFORD, NJ. AFTER THE DERAILMENT, CAUSED BY IRREGULAR TRACK CROSS LEVEL IN A CURVE, AND RESULTING IN FOUR CARS BEING DERAILED, THE CONDUCTOR, D. H. BUTLER, REPORTED SMELLING A SWEET ODOR WHEN INSPECTING FOR DAMAGE AND REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION FOR POSSIBLE CHEMICAL EXPOSURE. EMPLOYEE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT UNDERWOOD MEMORIAL HOSPITAL IN WOODBURY, NJ. IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE TANK CAR INDICATED ABOVE DID NOT CREATE THE ODOR ALLEGEDLY SMELLED BY MR. BUTLER. IT HAS ALSO BEEN DETERMINED THAT NONE OF THE OTHER CARS INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT CREATED THE ODOR ALLEGEDLY SMELLED BY MR. BUTLER.

SSA/HM HILL RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WHICH WAS CRACKED OPEN. MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE, R.M. STINE WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. GARY DOBBS, PARSONS, KS, THAT PRODUCT WAS NOTED RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF TANK CAR NATX 25770.  MANAGER STINE RESPONDED AND INSPECTION DETERMINED THE LIQUID WAS DRIPPING FROM UNDER THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING.  REMOVED INTACT CABLE SEAL "BCC-2855" AND FOUND THE PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THE BASE OF THE LIQUID VALVE WHERE IT ATTACHES TO THE FLANGE.  THE HEAT OF THE DAY HAD CAUSED A SLIGHT PRESSURE TO BUILD UP IN THE CAR AND LIQUID WAS PERCOLATING FROM THE THREADED JOINT.  PRESSURE WAS RELEASED AND VALVE WAS REMOVED AND THREADS CLEANED, TEFLON TAPE APPLIED, AND VALVE SECURED.  APPLIED SEAL UP X 140926 TO THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER. CHEMTREC, JOE MALAZZO, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SFVZ 731042, CONTAINING THREE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PRODUCTS (ALL CORROSIVES) AND OTHER NON REGULATED FREIGHT, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY CHECKPOINT INSPECTORS WHEN TRUCKER ATTEMPTED TO REMOVE TRAILER FROM THE LOS ANGELES HUB.  TRAILER WAS REJECTED AND ISOLATED.  INSPECTION OF LOAD REVEALED 2 LOCATIONS OF LEAKING PACKAGES.  NO LOAD SECUREMENTS OF ANY KIND HAD BEEN APPLIED TO THIS SHIPMENT.  ONE 55 GALLON POLY DRUM HAD BEEN CUT BY CONTACTING EXPOSED NAIL HEAD FROM PALLET DECK.  THE SIX 5 GALLON PAILS WERE PART OF 24 PAILS WHICH HAD MOVED REARWARD OFF EDGE OF PALLET AND WERE CRUSHED FROM THE OVERHEAD WEIGHT OF PALLET IN SECOND LAYER.  PAILS AND DRUMS WERE NOT SECURED TO THE PALLETS AND MOST DID NOT FILL THE DECK OF PALLET RESULTING IN BUILT-IN VOIDS WHICH PERMITTED LADING TO MOVE ON DECKS OF PALLETS. CONTAINERIZED CHEMICAL DISPOSAL HANDLED THE CLEANUP OF THIS SHIPMENT BETWEEN 1510 AND 1930.  ALL FREIGHT WAS REMOVED FROM TRAILER AND FLOOR AND AFFECTED AREAS WERE PROPERLY CLEANED.  THE LEAKING 55 GALLON DRUM WAS OVER PACKED INTO A POLYDRUM.  FOUR OF THE FIVE GALLON PAILS WERE PLACED INTO AN OPEN HEAD DOT 17-H DRUM, TWO EMPTY PAILS WERE PLACED INTO A PLASTIC DRUM LINER.  ALL WERE RETURNED TO LOAD.  ONE 30 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE WAS GENERATED FROM THIS CLEANUP OPERATION. SEE REPORT #92040224A.

column168: TRAILER 481 WAS BEING UNLOADED AT OUR DOCK.  DOCKWORKERS PUNCTURED THE LAST BARREL ON THE TRAILER (1315) HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE DOCK FOREMAN WHO THEN NOTIFIED THE TERMINAL MANAGER.  THE DOCK FOREMAN AND DOCKWORKER INHALED FUMES FROM THE LEAK TRYING TO CONTAIN THE LEAK ON THE TRAILER.  AT THE SAME TIME THE TERMINAL MANAGER NOTIFIED THE WICHITA FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT RESPONSE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED SECURED THE AREA CONTAINED THE SPILL NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL WITH SODA ASH AND RINSED DOWN THE AREA.  THE BARREL WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK.  THE EPA KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  THEY INSPECTED THE AREA AND CONCLUDED BY TEST THAT THERE WAS NO RUN OFF OR CONTAMINATION TO THE AREA.  THE DOT WAS NOTIFIED BY PHONE AT 1630 REPORT #12374 BRADSHAW. ARRANGEMENTS HAVEBEEN MADE FOR DISPOSAL THROUGH CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT OF KANSAS.  ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS.  DISCIPLINARY ACTION WILL BE TAKEN ON ALL INVOLVED FOR NOT FOLLOWING PROPER PROCEDURES.  USING INPROPER EQUIPMENT.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: OUR DRIVER, RONALD ANDERSON (WHO HAS 10 YEARS EXPERIENCE WITH KANEY TRANSPORTATION, INC.) DELIVERED A LOAD OF GASOLINE, BILL OF LADING NO 414048, TO CLARK #1768.  UPON ARRIVAL, RON STUCK THE TANK AND FOUND THAT ALL OF THE PRODUCT WOULDN'T FIT.  HE THEN CALLED HIS DISPATCHER TO FIND OUT THAT THERE WAS SOME CONFUSION ON WHICH STATION THIS LOAD WAS BEING DELIVERED TO.  THE DISPATCHERS INTENTION WAS TO DELIVER IT TO CLARK #435 IN CHICAGO HEIGHTS.  HOWEVER, SINCE RON WAS ALREADY AT CRETE, THEY DECIDED TO SPLIT THE LOAD BETWEEN THE TWO STATIONS. THE PREMIUM NO LEAD STICKING WAS MIS-CALCULATED BY OUR DRIVER. APPROXIMATELY 616 GALLONS WOULDN'T FIT.  THE TANK FILLED UP AND RAN OUT A SECOND FILL HOE THAT WAS NOT SEALED PROPERLY (BROKEN CAP).  APPROXIMATELY 31 TO 55 GALLONS CAME OUT ONTO THE DRIVE BEFORE OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO STOP THE PRODUCT FLOW.  THIS SECOND FILL IS ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE OF THE TRANSPORT AND AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL WAS ALSO CONCEALED BY A CAR AT THE GAS PUMP.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON MARCH 26, 1992 A PACKAGE [400 8078 2166] WAS STOPPED IN OUR ANCHORAGE FACILITIES SORT OPERATION BECAUSE OF A STRONG ODOR.  I WAS CALLED AND OPENED THE PACKAGE TO FIND 2 CANS OF PAINT LEAKING INSIDE.  I CALLED MEMPHIS CORPORATE OFFICE/DANGEROUS GOOD ADMINISTRATION AND THE FAA. INSPECTOR JOHN WHITE, WHO CAME AND SEIZED BOTH CANS FOR TESTING.  HE LATER CALLED AND INFORMED ME THAT THEY WERE FLAMMABLE AND TO DISPOSE OF THEM.

MANAGER, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE R.M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY DAVE COLLINS, RAMP SUPERVISOR, ADVISING THAT TRAILER KBSZ 930361 HAD BEEN GROUNDED AND CREWS NOTED A STRONG ODOR BUT NO VISIBLE LEAKAGE. TRAILER WAS ISOLATED AND HELD FOR INSPECTION. DUE TO FACT THAT MANAGER STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, CHIEF INSPECTOR AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES, A. D. MATY WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  INSPECTOR MATY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED 80 GALLON OPEN HEAD DRUMS IN TWO BAYS.  THE NOSE ROW HAD SHIFTED FROM 4 TO 18 INCHES TOWARD THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  DURING MOVEMENT THE OPEN HEAD DRUMS HAD BEEN OVERRIDING WHICH RESULTED IN A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED. MANAGER STINE CONTACTED TOM FLORES OF CHEMTREC AND REQUESTED SHIPPER CONTACT.  STEVE DRUMHELLER OF NORTHWEST ENVIROSERVICE CONTACTED MANAGER STINE AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR NORTHWEST ENVIROSERVICE PERSONNEL TO RESPOND.  RESPONDERS SECURED THE LOAD AND TRAILER WAS FORWARDED TO FREDONIA AND THEN RET URNED TO SEATTLE FOR PROPER CLEANING.
